<DIV1 TYPE="item"><PB REF="00000016.tif" N="xvi">

<PB REF="00000017.tif" N="1">
<HEAD>A Bestiary. [Arundel MS. 292, leaf 4 <I>a</I>.]</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Lion</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Natura leonis <I>j</I><SUP>a.</SUP></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;e leun stant on hille,</L>
<L>and he man hunten here,</L>
<L>O&eth;er &eth;urg his nese smel,</L>
<L N="4">Smake &eth;at he negge,</L>
<L>Bi wilc weie so he wile</L>
<L>To dele ni&eth;er wenden,</L>
<L>Alle hise fet steppes</L>
<L N="8">After him he fille&eth;,</L>
<L>Drage&eth; dust wi&eth; his stert</L>
<L>&eth;er he steppe&eth;,</L>
<L>O&eth;er dust o&eth;er deu,</L>
<L N="12">&eth;at he ne cunne is finden,</L>
<L>driue&eth; dun to his den</L>
<L>&eth;ar he him bergen wille.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><I>ij</I><SUP>a.</SUP></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>An o&eth;er kinde he haue&eth;,</L>
<L N="16">wanne he is ikindled</L>
<L>Stille li&eth; &eth;e leun,</L>
<L>ne stire&eth; he nout of slepe</L>
<L>Til &eth;e sunne haue&eth; sinen</L>
<L N="20">&eth;ries him abuten,</L>
<L>&eth;anne reise&eth; his fader him</L>
<L>mit te rem &eth;at he make&eth;.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000018.tif" N="2">
<HEAD><I>iij</I><SUP>a.</SUP></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;e &eth;ridde lage haue&eth; &eth;e leun,</L>
<L N="24">&eth;anne he lie&eth; to slepen</L>
<L>Sal he neure luken</L>
<L>&eth;e lides of hise egen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Significacio prime nature.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Welle heg is tat hil,</L>
<L N="28">&eth;at is heuen riche,</L>
<L>vre louerd is te leun,</L>
<L>&eth;e liue&eth; &eth;er abuuen;</L>
<L>wu &eth;o him likede</L>
<L N="32">to ligten her on er&eth;e,</L>
<L>Migte neure diuel witen,</L>
<L>&eth;og he be derne hunte,</L>
<L>hu he dun come,</L>
<L N="36">Ne wu he dennede him</L>
<L>in &eth;at defte meiden,</L>
<L>Marie bi name,</L>
<L>&eth;e him bar to manne frame.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><I>ij</I><SUP>a</SUP> et <I>iij</I><SUP>a.</SUP></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="40">&ETH;o ure drigten ded was,</L>
<L>and doluen, also his wille was,</L>
<L>In a ston stille he lai</L>
<L>til it kam &eth;e dridde dai,</L>
<L N="44">His fader him filstnede swo</L>
<L>&eth;at he ros fro dede &eth;o,</L>
<L>vs to lif holden,</L>
<L>wake&eth; so his wille is,</L>
<L N="48">So hirde for his folde;</L>
<L>He is hirde, we ben sep;</L>
<L>Silden he us wille,</L>
<L>If we heren to his word</L>
<L N="52">&eth;at we ne gon nowor wille,
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000019.tif" N="3">
<HEAD>THE EAGLE.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><I>Natura aquile.</I></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>KI&eth;en i wille &eth;e ernes kinde,</L>
<L>Also ic it o boke rede,</L>
<L>wu he newe&eth; his gu&eth;hede,</L>
<L N="56">hu he cume&eth; ut of elde,</L>
<L>Si&eth;en hise limes arn unwelde,</L>
<L>Si&eth;en his bec is al to-wrong,</L>
<L>Si&eth;en his <MILESTONE N="4b" UNIT="folio">fligt is al unstrong,</L>
<L N="60">and his egen dimme;</L>
<L>Here&eth; wu he newe&eth; him.</L>
<L>A welle he seke&eth; &eth;at springe&eth; ai</L>
<L>bo&eth;e bi nigt and bi dai,</L>
<L N="64">&eth;er-ouer he flege&eth;, and up he te&eth;,</L>
<L>til &eth;at he &eth;e heuene se&eth;,</L>
<L>&eth;urg skies sexe and seuene</L>
<L>til he cume&eth; to heuene;</L>
<L N="68">So rigt so he cunne</L>
<L>he houe&eth; in &eth;e sunne;</L>
<L>&eth;e sunne swide&eth; al his fligt,</L>
<L>and oc it make&eth; his egen brigt,</L>
<L N="72">Hise fe&eth;res fallen for &eth;e hete,</L>
<L>and he dun mide to &eth;e wete</L>
<L>Falle&eth; in &eth;at welle grund,</L>
<L>&eth;er he wurde&eth; heil and sund,</L>
<L N="76">and cume&eth; ut al newe,</L>
<L>Ne were his bec untrewe.</L>
<L>His bec is get biforn wrong,</L>
<L>&eth;og hise limes senden strong,</L>
<L N="80">Ne maig he tilen him non fode</L>
<L>him self to none gode,</L>
<L>&eth;anne go&eth; he to a ston,</L>
<L>and he bille&eth; &eth;er-on,</L>
<L N="84">Bille&eth; til his bec biforn</L>
<L>haue&eth; &eth;e wreng&eth;e forloren,</L>
<L>Si&eth;en wi&eth; his rigte bile</L>
<L>take&eth; mete &eth;at he wile.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000020.tif" N="4">
<HEAD><I>Significacio.</I></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="88">Al is man so is tis ern,</L>
<L>wulde ge nu listen,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS listlen.</NOTE></L>
<L>Old in hise sinnes dern,</L>
<L>Or he bicume&eth; cristen;</L>
<L N="92">and tus he newe&eth; him &eth;is man,</L>
<L>&eth;anne he nime&eth; to kirke,</L>
<L>Or he it bi&eth;enken can,</L>
<L>hise egen weren mirke;</L>
<L N="96">Forsaket &eth;ore satanas,</L>
<L>and ilk sinful dede;</L>
<L>Take&eth; him to ihesu crist,</L>
<L>for he sal ben his mede;</L>
<L N="100">Leue&eth; on ure loue[r]d crist,</L>
<L>and lere&eth; prestes lore;</L>
<L>Of hise egen were&eth; &eth;e mist,</L>
<L>wiles he drecche&eth; &eth;ore.</L>
<L N="104">his hope is al to gode-ward,</L>
<L>and of his luue he lere&eth;,</L>
<L>&eth;at is te sunne sikerlike,</L>
<L>&eth;us his sigte he bete&eth;;</L>
<L N="108">Naked falle&eth; in &eth;e funt-fat,</L>
<L>and cume&eth; ut al newe,</L>
<L>buten a litel; wat is tat?</L>
<L>his mu&eth; is get untrewe;</L>
<L N="112">his mu&eth; is get wel unku&eth;</L>
<L>wi&eth; pater noster and crede;</L>
<L>Fare he nor&eth;, er fare he su&eth;,</L>
<L>leren he sal his nede;</L>
<L N="116">bidden bone to gode,</L>
<L>and tus his mu&eth; rigten;</L>
<L>tilen him so &eth;e sowles fode,</L>
<L>&eth;urg grace off ure drigtin.<MILESTONE N="5a" UNIT="folio">
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter"><PB REF="00000021.tif" N="5">
<HEAD>THE SERPENT.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><I>Natura</I> serpentis. <I>j</I><SUP>a.</SUP></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="120">AN wirm is o werlde,</L>
<L>wel man it knowe&eth;,</L>
<L>Neddre is te name:</L>
<L>&eth;us he him newe&eth;,</L>
<L N="124">&eth;anne he is forbroken and forbroiden,</L>
<L>and in his elde al forwurden.</L>
<L>Faste&eth; til his fel him slake&eth;,</L>
<L>ten daies fulle,</L>
<L N="128">&eth;at he is lene and mainles</L>
<L>and iuele mai gangen;</L>
<L>he crepe&eth; cripelande for&eth;,</L>
<L>his craft he &eth;us ki&eth;e&eth;,</L>
<L N="132">Seke&eth; a ston &eth;at a &eth;irl is on,</L>
<L>Narwe, buten he nede&eth; him,</L>
<L>Nime&eth; vnne&eth;es &eth;urg,</L>
<L>for his fel he &eth;er lete&eth;;</L>
<L N="136">his fles for&eth; crepe&eth;,</L>
<L>walke&eth; to &eth;e water-ward,</L>
<L>wile &eth;anne drinken.</L>
<L>Oc he spewe&eth; or al &eth;e uenim</L>
<L N="140">&eth;at in his brest is bred</L>
<L>sro his birde time,</L>
<L>drinke&eth; si&eth;en inog,</L>
<L>and tus he him newe&eth;.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><I>ij</I><SUP>a.</SUP></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="144">&ETH;anne &eth;e neddre is of his hid naked,</L>
<L>and bare of his brest atter,</L>
<L>If he naked man se</L>
<L>ne wile he him nogt neggen,</L>
<L N="148">oc he fle&eth; fro him</L>
<L>als he fro fir sulde.</L>
<L>If he clo&eth;ed man se,</L>
<L>cof he waxe&eth;,</L>
<L N="152">For up he rigte&eth; him
<PB REF="00000022.tif" N="6"></L>
<L>redi to deren,</L>
<L>to deren er to ded maken,</L>
<L>if he it muge for&eth;en.</L>
<L N="156">wat if &eth;e man war wur&eth;e,</L>
<L>and weren him cunne,</L>
<L>figte&eth; wi&eth; &eth;is wirm</L>
<L>and f[a]re&eth; on him figtande;</L>
<L N="160">&eth;is neddre si&eth;en he nede sal,</L>
<L>make&eth; seld of his bodi,</L>
<L>and silde&eth; his heued;</L>
<L>litel him is of hise limes,</L>
<L N="164">bute he lif holde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>[<I>Significacio.</I>]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Knov cristene man</L>
<L>wat tu crist higtest</L>
<L>Atte kirke dure,</L>
<L N="168">&eth;ar &eth;u cristned were:</L>
<L>&eth;u higtes to leuen on him,</L>
<L>and hise lages luuien,</L>
<L>to helden wit herte</L>
<L N="172">&eth;e bodes of holi k[i]rke.</L>
<L>If &eth;u hauest is broken,</L>
<L>Al &eth;u forbre&eth;es,</L>
<L>forwur&eth;es and forgelues,</L>
<L N="176">Eche lif to wolden,</L>
<L>Elded art fro eche blis,</L>
<L>So &eth;is wirm o werld is;</L>
<L>Newe &eth;e fordi</L>
<L N="180">so &eth;e neddre do&eth;;</L>
<L>It is te ned.</L>
<L>Feste &eth;e of stedefastnesse,</L>
<L>and ful of &eth;ewes;</L>
<L N="184">and help &eth;e poure <MILESTONE N="5b" UNIT="folio">men</L>
<L>&eth;e gangen abuten.</L>
<L>Ne deme &eth;e nog[t] wurdi,
<PB REF="00000023.tif" N="7"></L>
<L>&eth;at tu dure loken</L>
<L N="188">up to &eth;e heueneward;</L>
<L>Oc walke wi&eth; &eth;e er&eth;e</L>
<L>mildelike among men;</L>
<L>no mod &eth;u ne cune,</L>
<L N="192">mod ne mannes vncost;</L>
<L>oc swic of sineginge;</L>
<L>and bote bid tu &eth;e ai,</L>
<L>bo&eth;e bi nigt and bi dai,</L>
<L N="196">&eth;at tu milce mote hauen</L>
<L>of &eth;ine misdedes.</L>
<L>&eth;is lif bitokne&eth; &eth;e sti</L>
<L>&eth;at te neddre gange&eth; bi,</L>
<L N="200">and tis is &eth;e &eth;irl of &eth;e ston</L>
<L>&eth;at tu salt &eth;urg gon.</L>
<L>Let &eth;in fil&eth;e fro &eth;e,</L>
<L>so &eth;e wirm his fel do&eth;;</L>
<L N="204">Go &eth;u &eth;an to godes hus</L>
<L>&eth;e godspel to heren,</L>
<L>&eth;at is soule drink,</L>
<L>sinnes quenching.</L>
<L N="208">Oc or sei &eth;u in scrifte</L>
<L>to &eth;e prest sinnes tine,</L>
<L>feg &eth;e &eth;us of &eth;i brest filde,</L>
<L>and feste &eth;e for&eth;ward</L>
<L N="212">fast at tin herte,</L>
<L>&eth;at tu firmest higtes.</L>
<L>&eth;us art tu ging and newe;</L>
<L>for&eth;ward be &eth;u trewe.</L>
<L N="216">Nede&eth; &eth;e &eth;e deuel nogt,</L>
<L>for he ne mai &eth;e deren nogt;</L>
<L>oc he fle&eth; fro &eth;e</L>
<L>so neddre fro de nakede.</L>
<L N="220">On &eth;e clo&eth;ede &eth;e neddre is cof,</L>
<L>and te deuel cliuer on sinnes;</L>
<L>Ai &eth;e sinfule
<PB REF="00000024.tif" N="8"></L>
<L>bisetten he wile,</L>
<L N="224">and wi&eth; al mankin</L>
<L>he haue&eth; ni&eth; and win;</L>
<L>wat if he leue haue</L>
<L>of ure heuen louerd</L>
<L N="228">for to deren us,</L>
<L>So he ure eldere or dede;</L>
<L>do we &eth;e bodi in &eth;e bale,</L>
<L>and bergen &eth;e soule,</L>
<L N="232">&eth;at is ure heued geuelic,</L>
<L>helde we it wur&eth;lic.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Ant</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><I>Natura formice.</I></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;e mire is magti,</L>
<L>mikel ge swinke&eth;</L>
<L N="236">In sumer and in softe weder,</L>
<L>So we ofte sen hauen;</L>
<L>In &eth;e heruest</L>
<L>hardilike gange&eth;,</L>
<L N="240">and renne&eth; rapelike,</L>
<L>and reste&eth; hire seldum,</L>
<L>and feche&eth; hire fode</L>
<L>&eth;er ge it mai finden,</L>
<L N="244">gaddre&eth; ilkines sed</L>
<L>bo&eth;en of wude and of wed,</L>
<L>Of corn and of gres,</L>
<L>&eth;at ire to hauen es,</L>
<L N="248">hale&eth; to hire hole,</L>
<L>&eth;at si&eth;en hire helpe&eth;</L>
<L>&eth;ar ge wile ben winter <MILESTONE N="6a" UNIT="folio">agen;</L>
<L>caue ge haue&eth; to crepen in,</L>
<L N="252">&eth;at winter hire ne derie;</L>
<L>Mete in hire hule &eth;at</L>
<L>&eth;at ge muge biliuen.</L>
<L>&eth;us ge tile&eth; &eth;ar,</L>
<L N="256">wiles ge time haue&eth;,
<PB REF="00000025.tif" N="9"></L>
<L>so it her telle&eth;;</L>
<L>oc finde ge &eth;e wete,</L>
<L>corn &eth;at hire qweme&eth;,</L>
<L N="260">Al ge forlete&eth; &eth;is o&eth;er se&eth;</L>
<L>&eth;at ic er seide;</L>
<L>Ne bit ge nowt de barlic</L>
<L>beren abuten;</L>
<L N="264">oc sune&eth; it and sake&eth; for&eth;,</L>
<L>so it same were.</L>
<L>get is wunder of &eth;is wirm</L>
<L>more &eth;anne man wene&eth;,</L>
<L N="268">&eth;e corn &eth;at ge to caue bere&eth;</L>
<L>al get bit otwinne,</L>
<L>&eth;at it ne forwur&eth;e</L>
<L>ne waxe hire fro,</L>
<L N="272">er ge it eten wille.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><I>Significacio.</I></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;e mire mune&eth; us</L>
<L>mete to tilen,</L>
<L>Long liueno&eth;e,</L>
<L N="276">&eth;is little wile</L>
<L>&eth;e we on &eth;is werld wunen:</L>
<L>for &eth;anne we of wenden,</L>
<L>&eth;anne is ure winter;</L>
<L N="280">we sulen hunger hauen</L>
<L>and harde sures,</L>
<L>buten we ben war here.</L>
<L>do we for&eth;i so do&eth; &eth;is der,</L>
<L N="284">&eth;anne be we derue</L>
<L>On &eth;at dai &eth;at dom sal ben,</L>
<L>&eth;at it ne us harde rewe:</L>
<L>Seke we ure liues fod,</L>
<L N="288">&eth;at we ben siker dere,</L>
<L>So &eth;is wirm in winter is,</L>
<L>&eth;an ge ne tile&eth; nummore.
<PB REF="00000026.tif" N="10"></L>
<L>&eth;e mire sune&eth; &eth;e barlic,</L>
<L N="292">&eth;anne ge fint te wete;</L>
<L>&eth;e olde lage we ogen to sunen,</L>
<L>&eth;e newe we hauen moten.</L>
<L>&eth;e corn &eth;at ge to caue bere&eth;,</L>
<L N="296">all ge it bit otwinne,</L>
<L>&eth;e lage us lere&eth; to don god,</L>
<L>and forbede&eth; us sinne.</L>
<L>It bet<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS <I>ben</I>.</NOTE> us er&eth;liche<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS ebriche.</NOTE> bodes,</L>
<L N="300">and bekued euelike;</L>
<L>It fet &eth;e licham and te gost</L>
<L>oc nowt o geuelike;</L>
<L>vre louerd crist it leue us</L>
<L N="304">&eth;at his lage us fede,</L>
<L>nu and o domesdei,</L>
<L>and tanne we hauen nede.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Hart</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><I>Natura cerui.</I></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;e hert haue&eth; kindes two,</L>
<L N="308">and forbisnes oc al so;</L>
<L>&eth;us it is on boke set,</L>
<L>&eth;at man clepe&eth; fisiologet.</L>
<L>He drage&eth; &eth;e neddre of de ston</L>
<L N="312">&eth;urg his nese up on-on,</L>
<L>of &eth;e stoc er of &eth;e ston,</L>
<L>for it wile &eth;erunder gon;</L>
<L>and swele&eth; it wel swi&eth;e,</L>
<L N="316">&eth;erof him brinne&eth; si&eth;en</L>
<L>of &eth;at attrie &eth;ing,</L>
<L>wi&eth;innen he <MILESTONE N="6b" UNIT="folio">haue&eth; brenning:</L>
<L>he lepe&eth; &eth;anne wi&eth; mikel list,</L>
<L N="320">of swet water he haue&eth; &eth;rist;</L>
<L>he drinke&eth; water gredilike</L>
<L>til he is ful wel sikerlike,</L>
<L>Ne haue&eth; &eth;at uenim non migt</L>
<L N="324">to deren him si&eth;en non wigt.
<PB REF="00000027.tif" N="11"></L>
<L>oc he werpe&eth; er hise hornes</L>
<L>in wude er in &eth;ornes,</L>
<L>and gingid him &eth;us &eth;is wilde der,</L>
<L N="328">So ge hauen nu lered her.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Significacio <I>prima</I>.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alle we atter dragen off ure eldere,</L>
<L>&eth;e broken drigtinnes word &eth;urg &eth;e neddre;</L>
<L>&eth;er-&eth;urg haue&eth; mankin</L>
<L N="332">bo&eth;en ni&eth; and win,</L>
<L>golsipe<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS kolsipe.</NOTE> and giscing,</L>
<L>giuernesse and wissing,</L>
<L>pride and ouerwene;</L>
<L N="336">swilc atter i-mene.</L>
<L>Ofte we brennen in mod,</L>
<L>and wur&eth;en so we weren wod;</L>
<L>&eth;anne we &eth;us brennen</L>
<L N="340">bihoue&eth; us to rennen</L>
<L>to cristes quike welle,</L>
<L>&eth;at we ne gon to helle;</L>
<L>drinken his wissing,</L>
<L N="344">it quenchet ilc siniging;</L>
<L>forwerpen pride euril[c] del,</L>
<L>so hert do&eth; hise hornes;</L>
<L>gingen us tus to godeward,</L>
<L N="348">and gemen us si&eth;en for&eth;ward.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Natura <I>ij</I><SUP>a.</SUP></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;e hertes hauen ano&eth;er kinde,</L>
<L>&eth;at us og alle to ben minde.</L>
<L>Alle he arn off one mode;</L>
<L N="352">For if he fer fecchen fode,</L>
<L>and he ouer water ten,</L>
<L>wile non at nede o&eth;er flen;</L>
<L>Oc on swimme&eth; bi-forn,</L>
<L N="356">and alle &eth;e o&eth;re folegen,
<PB REF="00000028.tif" N="12"></L>
<L>we&eth;er so he swimme&eth; er he wade&eth;:</L>
<L>Is non at nede &eth;at o&eth;er late&eth;,</L>
<L>Oc leige&eth; his skinbon</L>
<L N="360">on o&eth;res lendbon.</L>
<L>gef him &eth;at biforn te&eth;</L>
<L>Bilimpes for to tirgen,</L>
<L>Alle &eth;e o&eth;re cumen mide,</L>
<L N="364">and helpen him for to her[t]ien,</L>
<L>beren him of &eth;at water grund</L>
<L>up to &eth;e lond al heil and sund,</L>
<L>and for&eth;en here nede:</L>
<L N="368">&eth;is wune he hauen hem bi-twen,</L>
<L>&eth;og he an hundred to-giddre ben.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Significacio<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS signisicacio.</NOTE> <I>ij</I><SUP>a.</SUP></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;e hertes costes we ogen to munen,</L>
<L>Ne og ur non o&eth;er to sunen,</L>
<L N="372">oc eurilc luuen o&eth;er,</L>
<L>also he were his broder,</L>
<L>wur&eth;en stedefast his <MILESTONE N="7a" UNIT="folio">wine,</L>
<L>ligten him of his birdene,</L>
<L N="376">helpen him at his nede;</L>
<L>god giue&eth; &eth;er-fore mede:</L>
<L>we sulen hauen heuenriche,</L>
<L>gef we bitwixen<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS ben twixen.</NOTE> us ben briche:</L>
<L N="380">&eth;us is ure louerdes lage,</L>
<L>luuelike to fillen,</L>
<L>her-of haue we mikel ned,</L>
<L>&eth;at we &eth;ar-wi&eth; ne dillen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Fox</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><I>Natura wulpis.</I></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="384">A wilde der is</L>
<L>&eth;at is ful of fele wiles,</L>
<L>fox is hire to name,</L>
<L>for hire que&eth;sipe;
<PB REF="00000029.tif" N="13"></L>
<L N="388">husebondes hire haten,</L>
<L>for hire harm dedes:</L>
<L>&eth;e coc and te capun</L>
<L>ge fecche&eth; ofte in &eth;e tun,</L>
<L N="392">and te gandre and te gos,</L>
<L>bi &eth;e necke and bi &eth;e nos,</L>
<L>hale&eth; is to hire hole;</L>
<L>for-&eth;i man hire hatie&eth;,</L>
<L N="396">hatien and hulen</L>
<L>bo&eth;e men and fules.</L>
<L>Listne&eth; nu a wunder,</L>
<L>&eth;at tis der do&eth; for hunger:</L>
<L N="400">go&eth; o felde to a furg,</L>
<L>and falle&eth; &eth;ar-inne,</L>
<L>In eried lond er in er&eth;chine.</L>
<L>forto bilirten fugeles;</L>
<L N="404">Ne stere&eth; ge nogt of &eth;e stede</L>
<L>a god stund deies,</L>
<L>oc dare&eth; so ge ded were,</L>
<L>Ne drage&eth; ge non onde:</L>
<L N="408">&eth;e rauen is swi&eth;e redi,</L>
<L>wene&eth; &eth;at ge rotie&eth;,</L>
<L>and o&eth;re fules hire fallen bi</L>
<L>For to winnen fode,</L>
<L N="412">derflike wi&eth;uten dred;</L>
<L>he wenen &eth;at ge ded be&eth;,</L>
<L>he wullen<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>? billen</I> or <I>pullen</I>.</NOTE> on &eth;is foxes fel;</L>
<L>and ge it wel fele&eth;,</L>
<L N="416">ligtlike ge lepe&eth; up</L>
<L>and lette&eth; hem sone,</L>
<L>gelt hem here billing</L>
<L>ra&eth;e wi&eth; illing,</L>
<L N="420">tetogge&eth; and tetire&eth; hem</L>
<L>mid hire te&eth; sarpe,
<PB REF="00000030.tif" N="14"></L>
<L>Fret hire fille,</L>
<L>and go&eth; &eth;an &eth;er ge wille.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Significacio.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="424">Twifold forbisne in &eth;is der</L>
<L>to frame we mugen finden her,</L>
<L>warsipe and wisedom</L>
<L>wi&eth; deuel and wi&eth; iuel man;</L>
<L N="428">&eth;e deuel dere&eth; dernelike,</L>
<L>he lat he ne wile us nogt biswike,</L>
<L>he lat he ne wile us &eth;on non lo&eth;,</L>
<L>and bringe&eth; us in a sinne and ter he us slo&eth;,</L>
<L N="432">he bit us don ure bukes wille,</L>
<L>eten and drinken wi&eth; unskil,</L>
<L>and in ure skemting</L>
<L>he do&eth; ra&eth;e a foxing,</L>
<L N="436">he bille&eth; one &eth;e foxes fel<MILESTONE N="7b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>wo so telle&eth; idel spel,</L>
<L>and he tire&eth; on his ket</L>
<L>wo so him wi&eth; sinne fet,</L>
<L N="440">and deuel geld swilk billing</L>
<L>wi&eth; same and wi&eth; sending,</L>
<L>and for his sinfule werk</L>
<L>lede&eth; man to helle merk.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Significacio.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="444">&ETH;e deuel is tus &eth;e [fox] ilik</L>
<L>mi&eth; iuele breides and wi&eth; swik;</L>
<L>and man al so &eth;e foxes name</L>
<L>arn wur&eth;i to hauen same;</L>
<L N="448">for wo so seie&eth; o&eth;er god,</L>
<L>and &eth;enke&eth; iuel on his mod,</L>
<L>fox he is and fend iwis,</L>
<L>&eth;e boc ne lege&eth; nogt of &eth;is;</L>
<L N="452">So was herodes fox and flerd,</L>
<L>&eth;o crist kam in-to &eth;is middel-erd,
<PB REF="00000031.tif" N="15"></L>
<L>he seide he wulde him leuen on,</L>
<L>and &eth;ogte he wulde him fordon.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Spider</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Natura <I>aran&eacute;&eacute;</I>.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS <I>iran&eacute;&eacute;</I>.</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="456">Seftes sop ure seppande,</L>
<L>sene is on werlde,</L>
<L>lei&eth;e and lodlike,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS loldike.</NOTE></L>
<L>&eth;us we it leuen,</L>
<L N="460">manikines &eth;ing</L>
<L>alle manne to wissing.</L>
<L>&eth;e spinnere on hire swid ge weve&eth;,</L>
<L>feste&eth; atte hus rof,</L>
<L N="464">hire fodredes</L>
<L>o rof er on ouese,</L>
<L>so hire is on elde;</L>
<L>werpe&eth; &eth;us hire web,</L>
<L N="468">and weue&eth; on hire wise.</L>
<L>&eth;anne ge it haue&eth; al idigt.</L>
<L>&eth;e&eth;en ge driue&eth;,</L>
<L>hitt hire in hire hole,</L>
<L N="472">oc ai ge it biholde&eth;</L>
<L>til &eth;at &eth;er fleges faren</L>
<L>and fallen &eth;er-inne,</L>
<L>wi&eth;eren in &eth;at web,</L>
<L N="476">and wilen ut wenden;</L>
<L>&eth;anne renne&eth; ge rapelike,</L>
<L>for ge is ai redi,</L>
<L>nime&eth; anon to &eth;e net</L>
<L N="480">and nime&eth; hem &eth;ere,</L>
<L>bitterlike ge hem bit</L>
<L>and here bane wur&eth;e&eth;,</L>
<L>drepe&eth; and drinke&eth; here blod,</L>
<L N="484">do&eth; ge hire non o&eth;er god,</L>
<L>bute fret hire fille,</L>
<L>and dare&eth; si&eth;en stille.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000032.tif" N="16">
<HEAD><I>Significacio.</I></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;if wirm bitokne&eth; &eth;e man</L>
<L N="488">&eth;at o&eth;er biswike&eth;</L>
<L>on stede er on stalle,</L>
<L>stille er lude,</L>
<L>in mot er in market,</L>
<L N="492">er oni o&eth;er wise,</L>
<L>he him bit</L>
<L>&eth;an he him bale felle&eth;,</L>
<L>and he drinke&eth; his blod</L>
<L N="496">wanne he him dreue&eth;,</L>
<L>and &eth;o frete&eth; hem<NOTE PLACE="foot">? him.</NOTE> al,</L>
<L>&eth;an he him iuel werke&eth;.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>THE WHALE.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><I>Natura cetegrandie.</I></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Cethegrande is a fis</L>
<L N="500">&eth;e moste &eth;at in water is;</L>
<L>&eth;at tu <MILESTONE N="8a" UNIT="folio">wuldes seien get,</L>
<L>gef &eth;u it soge wan it flet,</L>
<L>&eth;at it were &aacute; neilond</L>
<L N="504">&eth;at sete one &eth;e se sond.</L>
<L>&eth;is fis &eth;at is vnride,</L>
<L>&eth;anne him hungre&eth; he gape&eth; wide,</L>
<L>vt of his &eth;rote it smit an onde,</L>
<L N="508">&eth;e swetteste &eth;ing &eth;at is o londe;</L>
<L>&eth;er-fore o&eth;re fisses to him dragen,</L>
<L>wan he it felen he aren fagen,</L>
<L>he cumen and houen in his mu&eth;,</L>
<L N="512">of his swike he arn uncu&eth;;</L>
<L>&eth;is cete &eth;anne hise chaueles luke&eth;,</L>
<L>&eth;ise fisses alle in suke&eth;,</L>
<L>&eth;e smale he wile &eth;us biswiken,</L>
<L N="516">&eth;e grete maig he nogt bigripen.</L>
<L>&eth;is fis wune&eth; wi&eth; &eth;e se grund,</L>
<L>and liue&eth; &eth;er eure heil and sund,
<PB REF="00000033.tif" N="17"></L>
<L>til it cume&eth; &eth;e time</L>
<L N="520">&eth;at storm stire&eth; al &eth;e se,</L>
<L>&eth;anne sumer and winter winnen;</L>
<L>ne mai it wunen &eth;er-inne,</L>
<L>So droui is te sees grund,</L>
<L N="524">ne mai he wunen &eth;er &eth;at stund,</L>
<L>oe stire&eth; up and houe&eth; stille;</L>
<L>wiles &eth;ar<NOTE PLACE="foot">? &eth;at.</NOTE> weder is so ille, </L>
<L>&eth;e sipes &eth;at arn on se fordriuen,</L>
<L N="528">lo&eth; hem is ded, and lef to liuen,</L>
<L>biloken hem and sen &eth;is fis,</L>
<L>an eilond he wenen it is,</L>
<L>&eth;er-of he aren swi&eth;e fagen,</L>
<L N="532">and mid here migt &eth;ar-to he dragen,</L>
<L>sipes on festen,</L>
<L>and alle up gangen;</L>
<L>Of ston mid stel in &eth;e tunder</L>
<L N="536">wel to brennen one &eth;is wunder,</L>
<L>warmen hem wel and heten and drinken;</L>
<L>&eth;e fir he fele&eth; and do&eth; hem sinken,</L>
<L>for sone he diue&eth; dun to grunde,</L>
<L N="540">he drepe&eth; hem alle wi&eth;-uten wunde.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Significacio.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;is deuel is mikel wi&eth; wil and magt,</L>
<L>So wicches<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS <I>witches.</I></NOTE> hauen in here craft,</L>
<L>he do&eth; men hungren and hauen &eth;rist,</L>
<L N="544">and mani o&eth;er sinful list,</L>
<L>tolle&eth; men to him wi&eth; his onde,</L>
<L>wo so him folege&eth; he finde&eth; sonde;</L>
<L>&eth;o arn &eth;e little in leue lage,</L>
<L N="548">&eth;e mikle ne maig he to him dragen:</L>
<L>&eth;e mikle, i mene &eth;e stedefast</L>
<L>in rigte leue mid fles and gast.
<PB REF="00000034.tif" N="18"></L>
<L>wo so listne&eth; deueles lore,</L>
<L N="552">on leng&eth;e it sal him rewen sore;</L>
<L>wo so feste&eth; hope on him,</L>
<L>he sal him folgen to helle dim.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Mermaid</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><I>Natura Sirene.</I><MILESTONE N="8b" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN &eth;e se senden</L>
<L N="556">selcu&eth;es manie;</L>
<L>&eth;e mereman is</L>
<L>a meiden ilike</L>
<L>on brest and on bodi,</L>
<L N="560">oc al &eth;uf ge is bunden;</L>
<L>fro &eth;e noule ni&eth;erward</L>
<L>ne is ge no man like,</L>
<L>oc fis to fuliwis</L>
<L N="564">mid finnes waxen.</L>
<L>&eth;is wunder wune&eth;</L>
<L>in wankel stede,</L>
<L>&eth;er &eth;e water sinke&eth;,</L>
<L N="568">sipes ge sinke&eth;,</L>
<L>and sca&eth;e &eth;uf werke&eth;</L>
<L>mirie ge singe&eth; &eth;is mere,</L>
<L>and haue&eth; manie stefnes,</L>
<L N="572">manie and sille,</L>
<L>oc it ben wel ille;</L>
<L>sipmen here steringe forgeten</L>
<L>for hire stefninge,</L>
<L N="576">slumeren and slepen,</L>
<L>and to late waken,</L>
<L>&eth;e sipes sinken mitte suk,<NOTE PLACE="foot">? <I>fuik.</I></NOTE></L>
<L>ne cumen he nummor up.</L>
<L N="580">Oc wise men and warre</L>
<L>agen cunen chare,</L>
<L>ofte arn atbrosten,</L>
<L>mid he[re] brest ouel;
<PB REF="00000035.tif" N="19"></L>
<L N="584">he hauen herd told of &eth;is mere</L>
<L>&eth;at tus unie-mete,</L>
<L>half man and half fis,</L>
<L>sum &eth;ing tokne&eth; bi &eth;is.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><I>Significacio.</I></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="588">Fele men hauen &eth;e tokning</L>
<L>of &eth;if forbisnede &eth;i[n]g,</L>
<L>wi&eth;uten weren wulues<NOTE PLACE="foot">? <I>sepes</I> or <I>lambes</I>.</NOTE> fel,</L>
<L>wi&eth;innen arn he wulues al;</L>
<L N="592">he speken godcundhede,</L>
<L>and wikke is here dede;</L>
<L>here dede is al vncu&eth;</L>
<L>wi&eth; &eth;at speke&eth; here mu&eth;;</L>
<L N="596">twifold arn on mode,</L>
<L>he sweren bi &eth;e rode,</L>
<L>bi &eth;e sunne and bi &eth;e mone,</L>
<L>and he &eth;e legen sone,</L>
<L N="600">mid here sage and mid here song</L>
<L>he &eth;e swiken &eth;er imong,</L>
<L>&eth;in agte wi&eth; swiking,</L>
<L>&eth;i soule wi&eth; lesing.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Elephant</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Natura <I>elephantis.</I></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="604">Elpes arn in Inde riche,</L>
<L>on bodi borlic berges ilike;</L>
<L>he to-gaddre gon o wolde,</L>
<L>so sep &eth;at cumen ut of folde,</L>
<L N="608">and behinden he hem sampnen</L>
<L>&eth;anne he sulen o&eth;re strenen;</L>
<L>Oc he arn so kolde of kinde</L>
<L>&eth;at no golsipe is hem minde,</L>
<L N="612">til he noten of a gres,</L>
<L>&eth;e name is mandragores,</L>
<L>Si&eth;en he bigeten on,
<PB REF="00000036.tif" N="20"></L>
<L>and two ger he &eth;er-mide gon.</L>
<L N="616">&eth;og he &eth;re hundred ger</L>
<L>on werlde more wuneden her,</L>
<L>bigeten he neuermor non,<MILESTONE N="9a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>so kold is hem si&eth;en blod and bon;</L>
<L N="620">&eth;anne ge sal hire kindles beren,</L>
<L>In water ge sal stonden,</L>
<L>In water to mid side,</L>
<L>&eth;at wanne hire harde tide,</L>
<L N="624">&eth;at ge ne falle ni&eth;er nogt,</L>
<L>&eth;at is most in hire &eth;ogt,</L>
<L>For he ne hauen no li&eth;</L>
<L>&eth;at he mugen risen wi&eth;.</L>
<L N="628">Hu he reste&eth; him &eth;is der,</L>
<L>&eth;anne he walke&eth; wide,</L>
<L>herkne wu it telle&eth; her,</L>
<L>for he is al unride.</L>
<L N="632">A tre he seke&eth; to fuligewis,</L>
<L>&eth;at is strong and stedefast is,</L>
<L>and lene&eth; him trostl[i]ke &eth;er-bi,</L>
<L>&eth;anne he is of walke weri.</L>
<L N="636">&eth;e hunte haue&eth; biholden &eth;is,</L>
<L>&eth;e him wille swiken,</L>
<L>wor his beste wune is,</L>
<L>to don hise willen;</L>
<L N="640">Sage&eth; &eth;is tre and under-set,</L>
<L>o &eth;e wise &eth;at he mai bet,</L>
<L>and hile&eth; it wel &eth;at he it nes war,</L>
<L>&eth;anne he make&eth; &eth;er-to char,</L>
<L N="644">him seluen sit olon, bihalt,</L>
<L>we&eth;er his gin him out biwalt.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS <I>biwarlt</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>&eth;anne cume&eth; &eth;is elp unride,</L>
<L>and lene&eth; him up on his side,</L>
<L N="648">slepe&eth; bi &eth;e tre in &eth;e sadue,</L>
<L>and fallen boden so to-gaddre;
<PB REF="00000037.tif" N="21"></L>
<L>gef &eth;er is noman &eth;anne he falle&eth;,</L>
<L>he reme&eth; and helpe calle&eth;,</L>
<L N="652">reme&eth; reufulike on his wise,</L>
<L>hope&eth; he sal &eth;urg helpe risen;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS si-sen; margin ri[sen].</NOTE></L>
<L>&eth;anne cume&eth; &eth;er on gangande,</L>
<L>hope&eth; he sal him don ut standen,</L>
<L N="656">Fike&eth; and fonde&eth; al his migt,</L>
<L>ne mai he it for&eth;en no wigt;</L>
<L>Ne canne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Read <I>Ne can he.</I></NOTE> &eth;an non o&eth;er,</L>
<L>oc<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS o; oc <I>in the margin</I>.</NOTE> reme&eth; mid his bro&eth;er,</L>
<L N="660">manie and mikle cume &eth;er sacande,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS <I>sacande</I>, margin se[cande].</NOTE></L>
<L>wenen him on stalle maken,</L>
<L>oc for &eth;e helpe of hem alle</L>
<L>ne mai he cumen so on stalle;</L>
<L N="664">&eth;anne remen he alle a rem,</L>
<L>so hornes blast o&eth;er belles drem,</L>
<L>For here mikle reming</L>
<L>rennande cume&eth; a gungling,</L>
<L N="668">ra&eth;e to him lute&eth;,</L>
<L>his snute him under pute&eth;,</L>
<L>and mitte helpe of hem alle</L>
<L>&eth;is elp he reisen on stalle;</L>
<L N="672">and tus<MILESTONE N="9b" UNIT="folio"> atbrested &eth;is huntes breid,</L>
<L>o&eth;e wise &eth;at ic haue gu seid.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>significacio.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;us fel adam &eth;urg a tre,</L>
<L>vre firste fader, &eth;at fele we:</L>
<L N="676">Moyses wulde him reisen,</L>
<L>migte it no wigt for&eth;en;</L>
<L>After him prophetes alle</L>
<L>migte her non him maken on stalle,</L>
<L N="680">on stalle, i seie, &eth;er he er stod,</L>
<L>to hauen heuenriche god.
<PB REF="00000038.tif" N="22"></L>
<L>he suggeden and sorgeden and weren in &eth;ogt,</L>
<L>wu he migten him helpen ovt;</L>
<L N="684">&eth;o remeden he alle onder <NOTE PLACE="foot">? <I>wonder</I> or <I>on der</I>.</NOTE>steuene</L>
<L>alle hege up to &eth;e heuene,</L>
<L>for here care and here calling</L>
<L>hem cam to crist heuen king;</L>
<L N="688">he &eth;e is ai in heuene mikel,</L>
<L>wur&eth; her man, and tus was litel,</L>
<L>drowing &eth;olede in ure manhede,</L>
<L>and tus adam he under-gede,</L>
<L N="692">reisede him up, and al mankin,</L>
<L>&eth;at was fallen to helle dim.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Turtledove</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><I>Natura turturis.</I></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>IN boke is &eth;e turtres lif</L>
<L>writen o rime, wu lagelike</L>
<L N="696">ge holde&eth; luue al hire lif time;</L>
<L>gef ge ones make haue&eth;,</L>
<L>fro him ne wile ge si&eth;en:</L>
<L>mune&eth; wimmen hire lif,</L>
<L N="700">ic it wile gu reden;</L>
<L>bi hire make ge sit o nigt,</L>
<L>o dei ge go&eth; and flege&eth;.</L>
<L>wo so seit he sundren ovt,</L>
<L N="704">i seie &eth;at he lege&eth;.</L>
<L>Oc if hire make were ded,</L>
<L>and ge widue wore,</L>
<L>&eth;anne flege&eth; ge one and fare&eth;,</L>
<L N="708">non o&eth;er wile ge more;</L>
<L>buten &oacute;ne go&eth; and one sit,</L>
<L>and hire olde luue abit,</L>
<L>In herte haue&eth; him nigt and dai,</L>
<L N="712">so he were oliue ai.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000039.tif" N="23">
<HEAD>Significacio.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>List ilk lefful<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS <I>lesful</I>.</NOTE> man her-to,</L>
<L>and herof ofte reche:</L>
<L>vre sowle atte kirke dure</L>
<L N="716">ches hire crist to meche,</L>
<L>he is ure soule spuse,</L>
<L>luue we him wi&eth; migte,</L>
<L>and wende we neure fro him-ward</L>
<L N="720">be dai ne be nigte;</L>
<L>&eth;og he be fro ure sigte faren,</L>
<L>be we him alle trewe,</L>
<L>non o&eth;er louerd ne leue<NOTE PLACE="foot">? <I>luue</I>.</NOTE> we</L>
<L N="724">ne non <MILESTONE N="10a" UNIT="folio">luue newe;</L>
<L>leue we &eth;at he liue&eth; ai</L>
<L>up on heuen-riche,</L>
<L>and &eth;e&eth;en he sal cumen eft,</L>
<L N="728">and ben us alle briche,</L>
<L>for to demen alle men,</L>
<L>oc nout on geuelike,</L>
<L>hise lo&eth;e men sulen to helle faren,</L>
<L N="732">hise leue to his riche.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Panther</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><I>Natura pantere.</I></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Panter is an wilde der,</L>
<L>Is non fairere on werlde her;</L>
<L>he is blac so bro of qual,</L>
<L N="736">mi&eth; wite spottes sapen al,</L>
<L>wit and trendled als a wel,</L>
<L>and itt bicume&eth; him swi&eth;e wel.</L>
<L>wor so he wune&eth; &eth;is panter,</L>
<L N="740">he fede&eth; him al mid o&eth;er der,</L>
<L>of &eth;o &eth;e he wile he nime&eth; &eth;e cul</L>
<L>and fet him wel til he is ful.</L>
<L>In his hole si&eth;en stille</L>
<L N="744">&eth;re dages he slepen wille,
<PB REF="00000040.tif" N="24"></L>
<L>&eth;an after &eth;e &eth;ridde dai</L>
<L>he rise&eth; and reme&eth; lude so he mai,</L>
<L>ut of his &eth;rote cume&eth; a smel</L>
<L N="748">mid his rem for&eth; oueral,</L>
<L>&eth;at ouer-cume&eth; haliweie</L>
<L>wi&eth; swetnesse, ic<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS it.</NOTE> gu seie,</L>
<L>and al &eth;at eure smelle&eth; swete,</L>
<L N="752">be it drie be it wete.</L>
<L>For &eth;e swetnesse off his onde,</L>
<L>wor so he walke&eth; o londe,</L>
<L>wor so he walked, er wor so he wune&eth;,</L>
<L N="756">Ilk der &eth;e him here&eth; to him cume&eth;,</L>
<L>and folege&eth; him up one &eth;e wold,</L>
<L>for &eth;e swetnesse &eth;e ic gu haue told.</L>
<L>&eth;e dragunes one ne stiren nout</L>
<L N="760">wiles te panter reme&eth; ogt,</L>
<L>oc daren stille in here pit,</L>
<L>als so he weren of dede offrigt.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Significacio.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>CRist is tokned &eth;urg &eth;is der,</L>
<L N="764">wos kinde we hauen told gu her;</L>
<L>for he is faier ouer alle men,</L>
<L>so euen sterre ouer er&eth;e fen;</L>
<L>ful wel he taunede his luue to man,</L>
<L N="768">wan he &eth;urg holi spel him wan,</L>
<L>and longe he lai her in an hole,</L>
<L>wel him dat he it wulde &eth;olen;</L>
<L>&eth;re daies slep he al on on,</L>
<L N="772">&eth;anne he ded was in blod and bon,</L>
<L>vp he ros and r&eacute;mede i-wis<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS <I>in wif</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>os helle pine, of heuene blis,</L>
<L>and steg to heuene uvemest,<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS <I>vueneft</I></NOTE></L>
<L N="776">&eth;er wune&eth; wi&eth; <MILESTONE N="10b" UNIT="folio">fader and holi gast.</L>
<L>Amonges men a swete [s]mel
<PB REF="00000041.tif" N="25"></L>
<L>he let her of his holi spel,</L>
<L>wor-&eth;urg we mugen folgen him</L>
<L N="780">in-to his godcundne se fin.</L>
<L>and &eth;at wirm ure wi&eth;erwine,</L>
<L>wor so of godes word is dine,</L>
<L>ne dar he stiren, ne noman deren,</L>
<L N="784">&eth;er<NOTE PLACE="foot">? &eth;e.</NOTE> wile he lage and luue beren.</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="chapter">
<HEAD>Dove</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="section">
<HEAD><I>Natura columbe</I> et significacio.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&ETH;E culuer haue&eth; costes gode,</L>
<L>alle wes ogen to hauen in mode,</L>
<L>seuene costes in hire kinde,</L>
<L N="788">alle it ogen to ben us minde,</L>
<L>ge ne haue&eth; in hire non galle,</L>
<L>simple and softe be we alle;</L>
<L>ge ne liue&eth; nogt bi lagt;</L>
<L N="792">Ile robbinge do we of bac.<NOTE PLACE="foot">? <I>hac = ac</I>, also.</NOTE></L>
<L>&eth;e wirm ge lete&eth; and liue&eth; bi &eth;e sed,</L>
<L>of cristes lore we haue ned;</L>
<L>wi&eth; o&eth;re briddes ge do&eth; as moder,</L>
<L N="796">so og ur ilk to don wi&eth; o&eth;er;</L>
<L>woning and groning is lic hire song,</L>
<L>bimene we us, we hauen don wrong.</L>
<L>In water ge is wis of heuekes come,</L>
<L N="800">and we in boke wi&eth; deules nome;</L>
<L>In hole of ston ge make&eth; hire nest,</L>
<L>In cristes milce ure hope is best.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV3>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 TYPE="item"><PB REF="00000042.tif" N="26">
<HEAD>Old Kentish Sermons. (<I>Laud. MS</I> 471.)</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="sermon">
<HEAD>SERMO IN DIE EPIPHANIE.</HEAD>
<P>CVm natus esset ihesus in betleem iude in diebus<MILESTONE N="128b" UNIT="folio"> herodis regis ecce magi ab oriente uenerunt ierosoli|mam dicentes. Vbi est qui natus est rex iudeorum. &para; We redeth i &thorn;o holi godespelle of te dai ase ure louerd god almichti i-bore was of ure lauedi seinte Marie i &thorn;e cite of bethleem. &thorn;et si sterre was seauinge of his beringe. swo apierede te &thorn;o &thorn;rie kinges of he&thorn;enesse. to-janes &thorn;o sunne risindde. And al swo hi bi-knewe his beringe bi &thorn;o sterre. swo hi nomen conseil be-tuene hem &thorn;et hi wolden gon for to hyne an-uri. and &thorn;et hi wolden offri him. gold. and stor. and Mirre. And al swo hi hedden aparailed here offrendes swo kam si sterre &thorn;et yede to-for hem in-to ierusalem. &THORN;ere hi speken to herodes and hym askede. wer was se king of gyus &thorn;et was i-bore. And herodes i-herde &thorn;et o king was i-bore &thorn;et solde bi king of geus. swo was michel anud. and alle hise men. for &thorn;et he was of-dred for to liese his king riche of ierusalem. &THORN;o dede he somoni alle &thorn;o wyse clerekes &thorn;et ku&thorn;e &thorn;e laghe and hem askede wer crist solde bien i-bore. Hi answerden &thorn;et ine ierusalem.<NOTE PLACE="foot">sic.</NOTE> for hit was swo i-seid and be-hote hwilem bi 
<PB REF="00000043.tif" N="27"> &thorn;o profetes. And al-swo herodes i-herde &thorn;is. swo spac te &thorn;o &thorn;rie kinges. and hem seide. Go&thorn; ha seide into bethleem and seche&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS <I>sechez.</I></NOTE> &thorn;et child. and wanne ye hit habbeth hi-funde swo an-uret hit. and efter &thorn;et cometh to me. and hic wille go and an-uri hit. <MILESTONE N="129" UNIT="folio">&THORN;et ne seide he nocht herodes for &thorn;et he hit wolde on-uri; ac for &thorn;et he hit wolde slon. yef he hit michte finde. &THORN;o kinges hem wenten and hi seghen &thorn;o sterre &thorn;et yede bi-fore hem. al-wat hi kam over &thorn;o huse. war ure louerd was. and al swo hi hedden i-fonden ure louerd; swo hin an-urede. and him offrede hire offrendes. Gold. and. stor. and Mirre. &THORN;o nicht efter &thorn;et aperede an ongel of heuene in here slepe ine metinge and hem seide and het. &thorn;et hi ne solde a-yen wende be herodes. ac be an o&thorn;er weye wende into hire londes. &para; Lordinges and leuedis &thorn;is is si glorius miracle. and si glorius seywinge of ure lordes beringe. &thorn;et us tel&thorn; &thorn;et holi godespel of te day. and ye muee wel under-stonde be &thorn;o speche of &thorn;e godspelle &thorn;et me sal to dai mor makie offrinke &thorn;an an o&thorn;ren dai. and &thorn;er-of us yeft ensample &thorn;o &thorn;rie kinges of he&thorn;enesse. &thorn;et comen fram verrene londes ure louerd to seche. and him makie offrinke. And be &thorn;et hi offrede gold. &thorn;et is cuuenable yeftte to kinge: seawede &thorn;et he was sothfast kink. and be &thorn;et hi offrede<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS <I>offr&emacr;de</I>.</NOTE> Stor. &thorn;et me offrede wylem be &thorn;o ialde laghe to here godes sacrefise; seawede &thorn;e[t] he was verray prest. And be &thorn;et hi offrede Mirre. &thorn;et is biter &thorn;ing. signefieth &thorn;et hi hedde be-liaue &thorn;et he was diadlich. &thorn;et diath solde suffri for man-ken. Nu i|hiereth wet signefieth &thorn;et Gold. &thorn;et. Stor. &thorn;et Mirre. And offre we Gostliche to ure lorde. &thorn;et [h]i offrede fles|liche. &THORN;et Gold &thorn;et is bricht and glareth ine &thorn;o bricht|nesse of &thorn;o sunne. signefieth &thorn;e gode belcaue. &thorn;et is bricht ine &thorn;e gode cristenemannes herte. Si gode beleaue licht and is bricht ine &thorn;o herte of &thorn;o gode Manne ase gold. Offre we &thorn;anne god almichti god gold. 
<PB REF="00000044.tif" N="28"> Be-leue we stede-fast-liche. &thorn;et he is fader and sune. and holy gost. is on-lepi god. Wo so hath beleaue ine gode swo offreth him god gold <MILESTONE N="129b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;et Stor signefied gode werkes.<NOTE PLACE="foot">sic, but <I>? biddinge</I>.</NOTE> for ase se smech of &thorn;e store wanne hit is i-do into &thorn;e uer&eacute;&eacute; and goth upward to &thorn;o heuene and to gode ward Swo amuntet si gode biddinge to gode of &thorn;o herte of &thorn;o gode cristenemanne. Swo we mowe sigge &thorn;et stor signefieth &thorn;e herte. and se smech luue of gode. Li &thorn;et Mirre<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>? and &thorn;et si Mirre</I> (or <I>Bi &thorn;et</I>, &amp;c.).</NOTE> &thorn;at is biter. and be &thorn;o biternesse defendet &thorn;et Cors &thorn;et is mide i-smered. &thorn;et no werm nel comme i-hende; signefiet &thorn;o gode werkes &thorn;et is biter to &thorn;o yemernesse of ure flesce. Si Mirre signefiet uastinge. for &thorn;o luue of gode wakie. go ine pelrimage. uisiti &thorn;e poure. and to sike. and to do alle &thorn;e gode &thorn;et me may do for godes luue. &thorn;o ilke &thorn;inges so bieth bitere to &thorn;o wrichede flessce. Ac al-so si mirre loket &thorn;et bodi &thorn;et no werm ne may &thorn;er i-hende come; so us defendet &thorn;o ilke<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS <I>il&egrave;ke</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;inges fram senne. and fram &thorn;e amonestement of &thorn;o dieule &thorn;et ha ne may us mis-do. Lordinges nu ye habbet i-herd &thorn;o signefiance of &thorn;o offringes &thorn;et maden &thorn;o &thorn;rie kinges of he&thorn;enesse to gode. hye<NOTE PLACE="foot">sic <I>? ye</I>.</NOTE> habbet to gode i-offred of yure selure. and of yure er&thorn;liche godes. Ne ne offreth him nacht on-lepiliche to day. ac alle &thorn;o daies i &thorn;o yere gostliche. Gold. and Stor. and Mirre. ase hic habbe i-told. Gold; fore Gode belaue. Stor; for holy urisun. Mirre. for gode werkes. &thorn;et bieth &thorn;o offringes. &thorn;et ure louerd be-seke&thorn; aueriche daye &thorn;o cristenemanne. and werefore se christenman yef has de&thorn;; of-seruet &thorn;o blisce of heuene. And ihesu crist &thorn;et for us wolde an er&thorn;e bi [i]-bore. and anured of &thorn;o &thorn;rie kinges of painime; he yeu[e] us his grace of &thorn;o holi gost in ure hertes wer-bi we moue hatie &thorn;o ileke &thorn;inges &thorn;et he hatedh. and lete &thorn;o ileke<NOTE PLACE="foot">read <I>ilke</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;inges &thorn;at he for-biet. and luuie &thorn;o ilek<NOTE PLACE="foot">read <I>ilke</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;inkes &thorn;at he luued. and do &thorn;o ilek &thorn;inges 
<PB REF="00000045.tif" N="29"> &thorn;at he h&oacute;&oacute;t. ine him so bileue and bidde and serui. &thorn;et we mowe habbe &thorn;o blisce of heueriche. Quod uobis prestare dignetur per. [&amp;c.]</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="sermon">
<HEAD>DOMINI[CA] SECUNDA POST OCTAVAM EPIPHANIE. SERMO EUAN.</HEAD>
<P>Nuptie facte sunt in chana <MILESTONE N="130" UNIT="folio">galil&eacute;&eacute;. <I>et</I> erat mater ihesu ibi. Vocatus est autem ihesus ad nuptias <I>et</I> discipuli eius. &para; &THORN;et holi godspel of to day us tel&thorn;. &thorn;et a bredale was i-maked ine &thorn;o londe of ierusalem. in ane cite &thorn;at was i-cleped Cane in &thorn;a time &thorn;at godes sune yede in er&thorn;e fles[ch]liche ac.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS has <I>fleslichc ar</I>. It looks like <I>ar</I> inserted between the lines.&mdash;G. P.</NOTE> To &thorn;a bredale was ure leuedi seinte Marie. and ure louerd ihesus crist and hise deciples. so iuel auenture &thorn;et wyn failede. at &thorn;ise bredale. &thorn;o seide ure leuedi seinte Marie. to here sune. hi ne habbet no wyn. And ure louerd answerde and sede to hire. Wat be-longeth hit to me o&thorn;er to &thorn;e wyman. Nu ne dorste hi namore sigge. ure lauedi. Hac hye spac to &thorn;o serganz &thorn;et seruede of &thorn;o wyne. and hem seyde. al &thorn;et he hot yu do; so do&thorn;. And ure louerd clepede &thorn;e serganz and seyde to hem. Fol vellet ha seyde. &thorn;os Ydres. &thorn;et is to sigge &thorn;os Cr&oacute;&oacute;s. o&thorn;er &thorn;os faten of watere. for &thorn;er were. vi. Ydres of stone. &thorn;et ware i-clepede ba&thorn;ieres wer &thorn;o gius hem wesse for clenesse. and for religiun. Ase &thorn;e custome was ine &thorn;o time. &thorn;o serganz uuluelden &thorn;o faten of watere and hasteliche was i-went into wyne. bie &thorn;o wille of ure louerde. &thorn;o seide ure lord. to &thorn;o serganz. Moveth to-gidere and bereth to Architriclin. &thorn;at was se &thorn;et ferst was i-serued. And al-so hedde i-drunke of &thorn;ise wyne &thorn;et ure louerd hedde i-maked of &thorn;e watere: ha niste nocht &thorn;e miracle. ac &thorn;o serganz wel hit wiste. &thorn;et hedde &thorn;et water i-brocht. &thorn;o seide Architriclin to &thorn;o bredgume. O&thorn;er men seyde he do&thorn; for&thorn; &thorn;et beste wyn &thorn;et hi habbe&thorn; ferst at here bredale. and &thorn;u hest ido &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000046.tif" N="30"> contrarie &thorn;et &thorn;u hest i-hialde &thorn;et beste wyn wat<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS <I>wath</I>.</NOTE> nu; &thorn;is was &thorn;e commencement of &thorn;o miracles of ure loruerde &thorn;et he made flesliche in er&thorn;e. and &thorn;o beleuede on him; his deciples. Ine sigge nacht &thorn;et hi ne hedden &thorn;er be|fore ine him beliaue; ac fore &thorn;e miracle &thorn;et hi seghe; was here beliaue &thorn;e more i-streng&thorn;ed. Nu ye habbe&thorn; i|herd &thorn;e Miracle. nu i-here&thorn; &thorn;e signefiance. &THORN;et water bi|tockned sc euele christeneman. <MILESTONE N="130b" UNIT="folio">for al-so &thorn;et water is natureliche schald and a-kel&thorn; alle &thorn;o &thorn;et hit drinke&thorn;; so is se euele christeman chald of &thorn;o luue of Gode. for &thorn;o euele werkes &thorn;et hi do&thorn;. Ase so is Lecherie. spus|breche. Roberie. Manslechtes. Husberners. Bakbiteres. and alle o&thorn;re euele deden. &thorn;urch wyche &thorn;inkes man of|serueth &thorn;et fer of helle. Ase godes oghe mudh hit seid. and alle &thorn;o signefied &thorn;et water; &thorn;et &thorn;urch. yemere werkes. o&thorn;er &thorn;urch yemer i-wil liesed &thorn;o blisce of heuene. &thorn;et wyn &thorn;at is naturelliche hot ine him-sclue; and an-het alle &thorn;o &thorn;et hit drinked; be-tokned alle &thorn;o &thorn;et bied an-h&eacute;&eacute;t of &thorn;e luue of ure lorde. Nu lordinges ure lord god almichti. &thorn;at hwylem in one stede. and ine one time flesliche makede of watere wyn; yet habbe&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS <I>hade&thorn;</I>.</NOTE> mani|time maked of watere wyn; gostliche. wanne &thorn;urch his grace maked of &thorn;o euele manne good man. of &thorn;e orgeilus umble. of &thorn;e lechur chaste. of &thorn;e ni&thorn;inge large. and of alle o&thorn;re folies; so ha maket of &thorn;o watere wyn. &thorn;is his si signefiance of &thorn;e miracle. Nu loke euerich man toward him-seluen. yef he<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS <I>he he</I>.</NOTE> is win; &thorn;et is to siggen yef he is an-heet of &thorn;o luue of gode. o&thorn;er yef he is water. &thorn;et is yef &thorn;u art chold of godes luue. yef &thorn;u art euel man; besech ure lorde &thorn;et he do ine &thorn;e his uertu. &thorn;et ha &thorn;e wende of euele into gode. and &thorn;et he do &thorn;e do swiche werkes &thorn;et &thorn;u mote habbe &thorn;o blisce of heuene. Quod uobis. prestare dignetur [&amp;c.].
</P>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="sermon"><PB REF="00000047.tif" N="31">
<HEAD>DOMINICA TERCIA POST OCTAVAM EPIPHANIE.</HEAD>
<P>Cvm descendisset ihesus de monte. secute sunt eum turbe multe. Et ecce leprosus ueniens adorabat eum dicens. Domine si uis; potes me mundare. &para; &THORN;et holi godspel of to dai us tel&thorn;. &thorn;et ure lord ihesus crist. ase he hedde i-yue &thorn;o newe laghe. in one montayne. and hedde i-maked &thorn;et formeste sarmun &thorn;et euerte made in er&thorn;e; suo him folgede michel folk. Swo kam a leprus. a sik man and onurede him and seyde. Lord. <MILESTONE N="131" UNIT="folio">lord ha seide yef &thorn;u wilt; &thorn;u me micht wel makie hool of mine lepre. of mine euele. And ure lord him seide and spredde his hond. and tok his lepre; hic wille seide ure lord &thorn;et &thorn;u bi clensed. and al-so ra&thorn;e he was i-warisd of his maladie. Nu lordinges &thorn;is is &thorn;e miracle &thorn;et &thorn;et godspel of te dai us tel&thorn;. ac great is &thorn;e tokningge. Se leprus signefie&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS <I>signefiez</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;o senuulle men. si lepre &thorn;o sennen. &thorn;et scab bi-tokned &thorn;o litle sennen. si lepre be-tokned &thorn;o grete sennen &thorn;et biedh diadliche. Ase so is lecherie. spusbreche. Gauelinge. Roberie. &THORN;efte. Glutunie. drunke|nesse. and alle &thorn;o sennen &thorn;urch wiche me liest &thorn;o luue of gode almichti and of alle his haleghen. &thorn;urch Scab nis nacht man and wyman deseiurd fram mannes felarede. Ne for &thorn;o litle sennen. &thorn;et no man hine ne mai loki. nis noon deseu[e]rd pardurableliche fram gode; ne fram holi chereche. for lepre is man deseu[e]rd of &thorn;o compainie of gode and of alle his angles. &thorn;at is to sigge for diadliche senne. Nu ye habbet i-herd &thorn;e miracle and wet hit be-tokned. Nu loke we yef we bie&thorn; clene of &thorn;ise lepre. &thorn;at is to siggen of diadliche senne. Se<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>? se leprus</I>.</NOTE> liest &thorn;e felarede of o&thorn;er men; for se &thorn;et sterft inne diadliche senne; so for liest &thorn;e compainie of gode. And yef ye bie&thorn; clene; loke&thorn; &thorn;et ye ne falle nocht. &thorn;et ye ne bie deseuerd fram &thorn;e felarede of gode almichti. &thorn;urch none euele werkes &thorn;urch none euele i-wil. And 
<PB REF="00000048.tif" N="32"> yef ye bie&thorn; leprus &thorn;urch diadliche senne. greded gode Merci; &thorn;et &thorn;o leprus yaf hel&thorn;e ine bodie; &thorn;et he us yeue gostliche hel&thorn;e. in ure saule. Come&thorn; to srifte for leted yure sennen and &thorn;er of bie&thorn; a-soiled. &thorn;anne sollie habbe &thorn;o hel&thorn;e of heuene. &thorn;at is lif with-uten ende. Quod uobis. prestare dignetur. per. [&amp;c.]</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="sermon">
<HEAD>DOMINICA QUARTA POST OCTAVAM EPIPHANIE.</HEAD>
<P>Ascendente ihesu in nauiculam. secuti sunt eum discipuli eius. Et ecce motus factus est magnus in mari. Ita ut nauicula operiretur fluctibus. Erat autem illis; uentus contrarius. <MILESTONE N="131b" UNIT="folio">&para; We redeth i &thorn;e holi godspelle of to dai &thorn;at ure lord ihesu crist yede one time into ane ssipe and ise deciples mid him in-to &thorn;e s&eacute;&eacute;. And so hi were in &thorn;o ssipe so a-ros a great tempeste. of winde. And ure lord was i-leid him don to slepe. ine &thorn;o ssipe. er &thorn;ane &thorn;is tempeste a-r&oacute;&oacute;s. Hise deciples hedde gret drede of &thorn;ise tempeste. so [hi] a-wakede hine. and seiden to him. lord saue us; for we perisset. And ha wiste wel &thorn;et hi ne hadde nocht gode beleaue ine him; &thorn;o seide to hem. wat dret yw folk of litle beliaue. &THORN;o a-ros up ure lord and tok &thorn;ane wynd and to s&eacute;&eacute;; and al-so ra&thorn;e hit was stille. And al-se &thorn;o men &thorn;et weren in &thorn;o ssipe hedde i-seghe &thorn;o miracle so awondrede hem michel. &THORN;is is si vaire miracle &thorn;et &thorn;et godspel of te day us tel&thorn;. &THORN;ere-fore sal hure be-liaue bie &thorn;e betere a-streng&thorn;ed. Ine swiche lorde &thorn;et siche miracle mai do and do&thorn; wanne he wile. Ac hit is us nyede &thorn;et se &thorn;et sucurede hem ine &thorn;a peril; &thorn;et us sucuri ine ure niedes. &THORN;et we clepie to him &thorn;et ha us helpe. and he hit wille do ble&thorn;eliche. yef we him bisecheth merci mid good i-wille al-so him-seluen seith bi &thorn;e holi writes. Salus populi ego sum. <I>et</I> cetera. Hic am ha sei&thorn; helere of &thorn;e folke. wanne hi to me clepiedh ine hire sorghen. and ine hire niedes hic hi sucuri and beneme hem al here euel with-ute ende. 
<PB REF="00000049.tif" N="33"> Grede we to him merci sikerliche. yef se deuel us wille a-cumbri &thorn;urch senne. &THORN;urch prede o&thorn;er &thorn;urch an-vie. o&thorn;er &thorn;urh wre&thorn;e. o&thorn;er &thorn;urch o&thorn;er manere of diadliche senne grede we to him Merci. and sigge we him lord sauue us &thorn;et we ne perissi. and &thorn;et he us deliuri of alle eueles. and &thorn;et ha yef us swiche werkes to done in &thorn;ise wordle. &THORN;et &thorn;o saulen of us mote bien isauued a domes dai. and gon to &thorn;o blisce of heuene. Quod ipse prestare dignetur. [&amp;c.]</P>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="sermon">
<HEAD>DOMINICA IN SEXAGESIMA. SERMO.</HEAD>
<P>SImile est regnum celorum homini patrifamilias. qui exijt primo mane conducere operarios in uineam suam.</P>
<P>&para; Hure lord godalmichti to us speke&thorn; ine &thorn;o holi<MILESTONE N="132" UNIT="folio"> godespelle of te day. and us seaweth one for|bisne. &thorn;et yef we uilleth don his seruise. &thorn;et we sollen habbe &thorn;o mede wel griat ine heuene. For so seyth ure lord ine &thorn;o godspelle of to dai. &thorn;et on good|man was. &thorn;at ferst uut-yede bi &thorn;e Moreghen for to here werkmen in-to his winyarde. for ane peny of fore|werde. and al so he hedde i-mad &thorn;ise forewerde; so ha sente hi into his wynyarde. so ha dede at undren and at midday also. &thorn;o &thorn;at hit was a-yen &thorn;an euen; so ha kam into &thorn;e Marcatte. so he fond werkmen &thorn;et were idel. &thorn;o seyde he to hem. W&eacute;&eacute; bie ye idel; and hie answerden; and seyde. lord; for we ne fonden te dai &thorn;at us herde. Go&thorn; nu ha seide se godeman into mine wynyarde; and hic &thorn;at richt is; yu sal yeue. &thorn;os yede into &thorn;ise wynyarde. mid &thorn;o o&thorn;re. &thorn;o &thorn;et hi wel euen. &thorn;o seide &thorn;e lord to his sergant. Clepe &thorn;o werkmen and yeld hem here trauail. and a-gyn to hem &thorn;at comen last. and go al to &thorn;o ferste. yef eueriche of hem ane peny. Se sergant dede &thorn;es lordes commandement. so paide &thorn;o werkmen and yaf euerich ane peny. And so hi seghen &thorn;o &thorn;et bi &thorn;e Morghen waren i-comen. &thorn;et hi 
<PB REF="00000050.tif" N="34"> &thorn;et waren last i-cume. Hedden here euerich ane peny; &thorn;o wenden hi more habbe; &thorn;o gruchchede hi a-menges hem. and seyden. &thorn;os laste on ure habbe&thorn; i-travailed. and &thorn;u his makest velaghes to us. &thorn;et habbeth al deai i-bye ine &thorn;ine wynyarde. and habbet&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot">sic.</NOTE> i-&thorn;oled &thorn;e berdene of &thorn;o pine. and of &thorn;o hete of al &thorn;o daie. &thorn;o ansuerede se gode man to on of hem. Frend ha seide ine do &thorn;e noon unricht. Wat for &thorn;ingketh &thorn;at hic do min i-wil; and al-so ure lord hedde i-told &thorn;ise forbisne; so he seide efter-ward. so sulle &thorn;o uerste bie last; and &thorn;o laste ferst. Fele bie&thorn; i-clepede; ac feaue bie&thorn; i|corn&eacute;&eacute;. Nu i-here&thorn; &thorn;e signefiance. &thorn;es godeman; be|tockne&thorn; god almichti ure lord. Se winyard be-tock|ne&thorn;. &thorn;e seruise of ure lorde. &thorn;e werkmen. be-tockne&thorn; alle &thorn;o &thorn;et do&thorn; cristes seruise. <MILESTONE N="132b" UNIT="folio">&thorn;o tides of &thorn;o daie; be-tokne&thorn; &thorn;e time of &thorn;is world. Bie &thorn;e Morghen i|herde ure lord werkmen in-to his winyarde. &thorn;o ha sente &thorn;e patriarches. ate begininge of &thorn;is wordl[e]. ine is seruise. &thorn;et &thorn;urch gode beleau&eacute;e him seruede. and seden his techinge to alle &thorn;o &thorn;et hi hedden hit to siggen. Al-so at undren. and at midday. i-herede he werkmen into is winyarde. &thorn;o ha sente be &thorn;o time &thorn;et Moyses was and Aaron. and i &thorn;e time of his prophetes dede he mani god man in-to his seruise; &thorn;et &thorn;urch griate luue to him helden. and deden his seruise. To-yenes &thorn;an<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS &thorn;&amacr;.</NOTE> euen; godalmichti i-hierde werkmen in-to his win|yarde. &thorn;o &thorn;at he alast of &thorn;is wordle naam fles and blod ine &thorn;e Maidene seinte Marie. and seauede ine &thorn;is world. &thorn;o fond he Men. &thorn;et al day hedden i-be idel. Werefore he fond &thorn;et he&thorn;en folk &thorn;et be &thorn;o time &thorn;et was i-go; hedden i-be ut of godes be-liaue. and of his luue. and of his seruise. Hi ne hedden nocht i-be idel for to done &thorn;o deueles werkes. Ac &thorn;ere-fore seith &thorn;et godspel &thorn;et hedden i-be idel; &thorn;o &thorn;et hi nedden bi-leued ane god almichti. ne him louie ne him serui. For al &thorn;at is ine 
<PB REF="00000051.tif" N="35"> &thorn;is wordle. &thorn;et man is. bote yef ha luuie god almichti. and him serui; al hit him may &thorn;enche for-lore and idelnesse. &thorn;o a-resunede ure lord &thorn;e paens be ise apo|stles. vre-fore hi hedden i-be so longe idel. &thorn;o &thorn;et hi ne hedden i-be in his seruise; &thorn;o ansuerden &thorn;e paens; &thorn;et non ne hedden i-herd hij. &thorn;et is to sigge &thorn;et hi ne hedden neuer-te i-heed prophete ne apostle ne prechur. &thorn;et hem seaude ne hem tachte hu [h]i solden ine gode beleue ne him serui. Go&thorn; a seide ure lord inte mine Winyarde. &thorn;et is inte mine beleaue. and hic yw sal yeue yure peni &thorn;et is heueriche blisce. &thorn;o he-&thorn;en men yeden be &thorn;a daghen into cristes seruise; and we &thorn;et of hem bie&thorn; i-cume. and habbe&thorn; cristendom under-fonge; bie&thorn; i-entred in-to cristes seruise &thorn;ere-fore we sollen habbe ure peni &thorn;et is &thorn;e blisce of heuene. <MILESTONE N="133" UNIT="folio">Al-so wel ase &thorn;o &thorn;et comen bi &thorn;e Morghen. for also we hopie&thorn; for te habbe heueriche blisce; ase &thorn;o patriarches and &thorn;o prophetes. and &thorn;o apostles and &thorn;o gode men &thorn;et hwilem ine &thorn;is world godalmichti serueden. So as we habe&thorn; i-seid of diuers wordles. &thorn;et god almichti dede werkmen into his winyarde; so we mowe sigge of &thorn;o elde of eueriche men. For god almichti de&thorn; werkmen into his winyarde bi &thorn;e Morghen. wanne ha clepe&thorn; of swiche &thorn;er bie&thorn; into his seruise ine here childhede. Wanne hi of &thorn;is world wende&thorn;. beswo &thorn;et hi ne be ine no diadlich senne. At undren ha sent men into his winyarde. &thorn;et a turne&thorn; into his seruise. of age of man. At Middai wanne &thorn;o dai is al &thorn;er hotestd be-tokned &thorn;o men of xxx<SUP>ti</SUP>. wyntre. o&thorn;er of furti. for &thorn;e nature of Man is of greater streng&thorn;e and of greater hete ine &thorn;o age. Se euen bi-tockne&thorn;. elde of Man. &thorn;et is se ende of &thorn;e liue. Vre lord de&thorn; werkmen in-to his winyarde a-genes &thorn;o euen; Wanne fele ine here elde wende&thorn; ut of here senne in-to cristes seruise. As so<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>? al so.</I></NOTE> solle hi habbe &thorn;o blisce of heuene; ase &thorn;o &thorn;et ferst comen into &thorn;e 
<PB REF="00000052.tif" N="36"> winyyarde. Nocht for &thorn;an for &thorn;ise griate bunte &thorn;et ure lord yef&thorn; ne solde no-man targi for to wende to godal|michti ne him to serui. for al so seid &thorn;et holi writ &thorn;et non ne wot &thorn;ane dai of his dia&thorn;e. for Man mai longe liues wene and ofte him leghe&thorn; se wrench. Nu gode men ye habbe&thorn; i-herd &thorn;et godspel and &thorn;e forbisne. Nu loke&thorn; yef ye bie&thorn; with-inne &thorn;o winyarde. &thorn;et is &thorn;et yef ye bie&thorn; ine godes seruise yef ye bie&thorn; with ute diadliche senne yef ye hatied &thorn;at he<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS <I>he he</I>.</NOTE> hate&thorn;. yef ye luuie&thorn; &thorn;et he luue&thorn;. and do&thorn; &thorn;et he hot. and bute ye do; ye bie&thorn; hut of hiswinyarde. &thorn;et is ut of his seruise. and ye do&thorn; &thorn;et ure lord h&oacute;&oacute;t. so ye of-serue&thorn; &thorn;ane peni. &thorn;et is heueriche blisce. ye of-serue&thorn; &thorn;et good &thorn;et noon herte ne may i-&thorn;enche ne noon yare i-here ne tunge telle. &thorn;o blisce &thorn;et god <MILESTONE N="133b" UNIT="folio">halt alle &thorn;o &thorn;et hine luuie&thorn;. &thorn;ider lord granti us to cumene. Quod ipse prestare dignetur. per. [&amp;c.]<NOTE PLACE="end">[Follows:&mdash;<B>Sermo in</B> quadragesimam; (in Latin).]</NOTE>
</P>

</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="1" TYPE="item"><PB REF="00000053.tif" N="37">
<HEAD>I. The Passion of our Lord. [<I>Jesus College</I> (<I>Oxford</I>) <I>MS I. Arch. I.</I> 29, <I>leaf</I> 217.]</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="section">
<HEAD>Ici cumence la passyun ihesu crist en engleys. Incipit prologus.</HEAD>
<L>Ihere&thorn; nv one lutele tale. &thorn;at ich eu wille telle.</L>
<L>As we vynde&thorn; hit iwrite. in &thorn;e godspelle.</L>
<L>Nis hit nouht of karlemeyne ne of &thorn;e Duzeper.</L>
<L N="4">Ac of cristes &thorn;ruwinge. &thorn;et he &thorn;olede her.</L>
<L>Al volk wes to-dreued. so schep beo&thorn; in &thorn;e wolde.</L>
<L>Lute ymvnde. hi hedde of gode. heore heorten weren so colde.</L>
<L>He &thorn;et is. and euer wes. in heuene myd his fadere.</L>
<L N="8">Ful lowe he alyhte. for bryngen heom to-gadere.</L>
<L>&THORN;urst. and hunger. chele. and hete. &thorn;is beo&thorn; stronge pyne.</L>
<L>&THORN;eos he &thorn;olede al vor vs. &thorn;at turnde water to wyne.</L>
<L>&THORN;rytty wyntre and more. he wes among Monkunne.</L>
<L N="12">Seo&thorn;&thorn;e &thorn;at Mayde hyne yber. al wi&thorn;-vte sunne.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he hedde so longe ibeo. ine wrecche lyue &thorn;isse.</L>
<L>He wes swy&thorn;e of-longed. to his fader blysse.</L>
<L>Nouht for &thorn;an &thorn;at he nedde. in his godcunnesse.</L>
<L N="16">Ac he wolde &thorn;at we myd him. bo&thorn;e more and lesse.</L>
<L>Heo habbe scolde. and so we Mvwe. ne &thorn;erf&thorn; &thorn;er non adrede.</L>
<L>Yf we vs wyte&thorn; from heued-sunne. and do&thorn; al by his rede.</L>
<L>&THORN;e louerd &thorn;et alle &thorn;ing ischop.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS iscohp.</NOTE> to &thorn;ere blysse vs brynge.</L>
<L N="20">Nv bigynne&thorn; vre tale. nys hit no lesynge.
</L>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="section"><PB REF="00000054.tif" N="38">
<HEAD>Her biginne&thorn; cristes &thorn;rowynge .i. sa passyun.</HEAD>
<L>LEuedi &thorn;u bere &thorn;at beste child. &thorn;at euer wes ibore.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e he makede his moder. vor he &thorn;e hedde yc&oacute;re.</L>
<L>Adam and his ofsprung. al hit were fur-lore.</L>
<L N="24">Yf &thorn;i sune n&eacute;re. iblessed &thorn;u beo &thorn;er-vore.</L>
<L>After &thorn;at he wes yuolled. in &thorn;e flum iurdan.</L>
<L>Of &thorn;e prophete &thorn;at hatte seynt iohan.</L>
<L>&THORN;e holy gost hyne ledde. vp in-to &thorn;e wolde.</L>
<L N="28">For to beon yuonded. of sathanas &thorn;en olde.</L>
<L>&THORN;er he wes fourty<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS forurty.</NOTE> dawes. al wi&thorn;-vte mete.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he hedde heom yuast. &thorn;o luste hym &eacute;te.</L>
<L>&THORN;er hym com sathanas. &thorn;at is ful of hete.<MILESTONE N="217b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="32">Mid his false wordes. he gon myd him to speke.</L>
<L>A&thorn;re cunne wise. he vondi hyne bi-gon.</L>
<L>As he vondede Adam. and hyne ouer-com.</L>
<L>M[id] yuernesse and prude. and yssyng wes &thorn;at on.</L>
<L N="36">He nuste nouht. &thorn;at he wes. bo&thorn;e god and mon.</L>
<L>&THORN;o seyde ihesu crist. &thorn;et is godes sune.</L>
<L>Ga abak sathanas. to hwan artu ycume.</L>
<L>Anon he hyne byleuede. more to vondy.</L>
<L N="40">And &thorn;er comen engles. hym to seruy.</L>
<L>&THORN;o he bygon to prechi. wel mylde weren his dede.</L>
<L>He ches hym twolue yu&eacute;re. myd him vor to lede.</L>
<L>Summe hi weren wyse. and duden al bi his rede.</L>
<L N="44">Ac on hyne bitrayede. &thorn;at et of his brede.</L>
<L>Alle men he tauhte to holde treowe luue.</L>
<L>Erest to god almyhti. &thorn;at is vs alle abuve.</L>
<L>Se&thorn;&thorn;e to luuye his euenyng. al so hym seolue wolde.</L>
<L N="48">And euervich beo to o&thorn;re. bo&thorn;e treowe and holde.</L>
<L>Mvchel volk hym vulede. wyte ye for hwon.</L>
<L>Summe to beon hole. of vuele &thorn;et wes heom on.</L>
