<DIV1 N="25" TYPE="item">
<DIV2 TYPE="version">

<PB REF="00000202.tif" N="186">
<HEAD>XXV. A lutel soth Sermun. [<I>Cotton MS. Caligula A ix, leaf</I> 248, <I>back.</I>]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Herknied alle gode men</L>
<L>And stille sitte&thorn; adun.</L>
<L>And ich eou wule tellen</L>
<L N="4">a lutel sermun.<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. sermum.</NOTE></L>
<L>Wel we witen alle.</L>
<L>&thorn;ag ich eou no&yogh;t ne telle;</L>
<L>Hu adam vre vorme fader.</L>
<L N="8">adun vel in-to helle.</L>
<L>Schomeliche he uor-les</L>
<L>&thorn;e blisse &thorn;at he hedde.</L>
<L>To &yogh;iuernesse and prude.</L>
<L N="12">none neode he nedde.</L>
<L>He nom &thorn;en appel of &thorn;e tre.</L>
<L>&thorn;at him for-bode was.</L>
<L>So reusful dede idon</L>
<L N="16">neuer non nas.</L>
<L>He made him in-to helle falle.</L>
<L>And efter him his children alle.</L>
<L>&THORN;er he was fort ure drihte.</L>
<L N="20">Hine bohte mid his mihte.</L>
<L>He hine alesede mid his blode.</L>
<L>&THORN;at he sc[h]edde<NOTE PLACE="marg">The <I>h</I> written above the line in a later hand.</NOTE> up-on &thorn;e rode.</L>
<L>To de&thorn;e he &yogh;ef him for us alle.</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;o we weren so stronge at-falle</L>
<L>Alle bac-biteres.</L>
<L>wendet to helle.</L>
<L>Robberes. and reueres.</L>
<L N="28">and &thorn;e monquelle.</L>
<L>Lechurs. and horlinges.</L>
<L>&thorn;ider sculen wende.
<PB REF="00000204.tif" N="188"></L>
<L>And &thorn;er heo sculen wunien.</L>
<L N="32">euere buten ende.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;eos false chepmen.</L>
<L>&thorn;e feond heom wule habbe.</L>
<L>Bachares. and brueres.</L>
<L N="36">for alle men heo gabbe.</L>
<L>Lo&yogh;e heo holdet hore galun.</L>
<L>mid berme heo hine fulle&thorn;.</L>
<L>And euer of &thorn;e purse.</L>
<L N="40">&thorn;at seluer heo tulle&thorn;.</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e heo make&thorn; feble.</L>
<L>heore bred. and heore ale.</L>
<L>Habben heo &thorn;at seluer;</L>
<L N="44">ne tellet heo neuer tale.</L>
<L>Godemen for godes luue.</L>
<L>bileue&thorn; suche sunne.</L>
<L>For atten ende hit bi-nime&thorn;</L>
<L N="48">heueriche wunne.</L>
<L>Alle prestes wifes.</L>
<L>ich wot heo beo&thorn; for-lore.</L>
<L>&THORN;es persones ich wene;</L>
<L N="52">ne beo&thorn; heo no&yogh;t for-bore.<MILESTONE N="249" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ne &thorn;eos prude &yogh;ungemen.</L>
<L>&thorn;at luuie&thorn; malekin.</L>
<L>And &thorn;eos prude maidenes.</L>
<L N="56">&thorn;at luuie&thorn; Ianekin.</L>
<L>At chirche. and at cheping.</L>
<L>hwanne heo to-gadere come.</L>
<L>Heo rune&thorn; to-gaderes.</L>
<L N="60">and speke&thorn; of derne luue.</L>
<L>Hwenne heo to chirche come&thorn;.</L>
<L>to &thorn;e haliday.</L>
<L>Eueruch wile his leof iseon.</L>
<L N="64">&thorn;er &yogh;ef<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS. &yogh;e&thorn;</NOTE> he may.</L>
<L>Heo bi-holde&thorn; wadekin.</L>
<L>mid swi&thorn;e gled eye.
<PB REF="00000206.tif" N="190"></L>
<L>Atom his hire pater noster.</L>
<L N="68">biloken in hire teye.</L>
<L>Masses and matines.</L>
<L>ne kepe&thorn; heo nouht.</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L N="72">. . . . .</L>
<L>Robin wule Gilot.</L>
<L>leden to &thorn;en ale.</L>
<L>And sitten &thorn;er to-gederes.</L>
<L N="76">and tellen heore tale.</L>
<L>He mai quiten hire ale.</L>
<L>and so&thorn;en do &thorn;at gome.</L>
<L>An eue to go mid him.</L>
<L N="80">ne &thorn;u[n]chet hire no schome.</L>
<L>Hire sire and hire dame.</L>
<L>&thorn;rete&thorn; hire to bete.</L>
<L>Nule heo for-go Robin.</L>
<L N="84">for al heore &thorn;rete.</L>
<L>Euer heo wile hire schere.</L>
<L>ne com hire nomon neh.</L>
<L>Fort &thorn;at hire wombe.</L>
<L N="88">up arise an heh.</L>
<L>Godemen for godes luue.</L>
<L>bi-leue&thorn; eoure sunne.</L>
<L>For aten ende hit bi-nime&thorn;.</L>
<L N="92">heueriche wunne.</L>
<L>Bidde we seinte marie.</L>
<L>for hire milde mode.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e teres &thorn;at heo wep.</L>
<L N="96">for hire sone blode.</L>
<L>Al so wis so he god his.</L>
<L>for hire erndinge.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e blisse of heuene.</L>
<L N="100">he us alle bringe.</L>
<TRAILER>A M E N.</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV2>

<DIV2 TYPE="version">

<PB REF="00000203.tif" N="187">
<HEAD>XXV. A lutel soth Sermun. [<I>Jesus Coll. MS.</I> 29, <I>leaf</I> 258.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Herkne&thorn; alle gode men</L>
<L>and stylle sitte&thorn; a-dun.</L>
<L>And ich ou wile tellen</L>
<L N="4">a lutel so&thorn; sermun.</L>
<L>Wel we wuten alle.</L>
<L>&thorn;ey ich ou nouht ne telle.</L>
<L>Hw Adam vre vorme fader.</L>
<L N="8">a-dun feol in-to helle.</L>
<L>Schomeliche he forles.</L>
<L>&thorn;e blisse &thorn;at he hedde.</L>
<L>To yuernesse and prude.</L>
<L N="12">none neode he nedde.</L>
<L>He nom &thorn;an appel of &thorn;e treo.</L>
<L>&thorn;at him forbode was.</L>
<L>So reu&thorn;ful dede idon.</L>
<L N="16">neuer non nas.</L>
<L>He made him in-to helle falle.</L>
<L>And after him his children alle.</L>
<L>&THORN;er he wes fort vre drihte.</L>
<L N="20">Hyne bouhte myd his myhte.</L>
<L>He hine alesede myd his blode.</L>
<L>&THORN;at he schedde vp-on &thorn;e rode.</L>
<L>To de&thorn;e he yef him for vs alle.</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;o we weren so strong at-falle.</L>
<L>Alle bakbytares.</L>
<L>heo wende&thorn; to helle.</L>
<L>Robbares. and reuares.</L>
<L N="28">and &thorn;e Monquelle.</L>
<L>Lechurs. and horlyngs.</L>
<L>&thorn;ider schulle&thorn; wende.
<PB REF="00000205.tif" N="189"></L>
<L>And &thorn;er heo schulle wunye.</L>
<L N="32">euer buten ende.</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;eos false chapmen.</L>
<L>&thorn;e feond heom wule habbe.</L>
<L>Bakares and breowares.</L>
<L N="36">for alle men heo gabbe.</L>
<L>Lowe heo holde&thorn; heore galun.</L>
<L>Mid beorme heo hine fulle&thorn;.</L>
<L>And euer of &thorn;e purse.</L>
<L N="40">&thorn;at seoluer heo tulle&thorn;.</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e heo make&thorn; feble.</L>
<L>heore bred and heore ale.</L>
<L>Habbe heo &thorn;at seoluer.</L>
<L N="44">ne telle&thorn; heo neuer tale.</L>
<L>Gode men for godes luue.</L>
<L>bileue&thorn; sucche sunne.</L>
<L>For at &thorn;en ende hit bi-nyme&thorn;.</L>
<L N="48">heueriche wunne.</L>
<L>Alle preostes wives.</L>
<L>ich wot heo beo&thorn; for-lore.</L>
<L>&THORN;es persones ich wene.</L>
<L N="52">ne beo&thorn; heo nouht for-bore.</L>
<L>Ne &thorn;eos prude yongemen.</L>
<L>&thorn;at luuye&thorn; Malekyn.</L>
<L>And &thorn;eos prude maydenes.<MILESTONE N="258b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="56">&thorn;at luuye&thorn; ianekyn.</L>
<L>At chireche and at chepyng.</L>
<L>hwanne heo to-gadere c&oacute;me.</L>
<L>Heo rune&thorn; to-gaderes.</L>
<L N="60">and speke&thorn; of derne luue.</L>
<L>Hwenne heo to chirche cume&thorn;.</L>
<L>to &thorn;on holy daye.</L>
<L>Euervych wile his leof i-seo.</L>
<L N="64">&thorn;er yef he may.</L>
<L>Heo biholde&thorn; watekin.</L>
<L>Mid swi&thorn;e gled eye.
<PB REF="00000207.tif" N="191"></L>
<L>At hom is hire pater noster.</L>
<L N="68">biloken in hire teye.</L>
<L>Masses and Matynes.</L>
<L>ne kepe&thorn; heo nouht.</L>
<L>For wilekyn and watekyn.</L>
<L N="72">beo&thorn; in hire &thorn;ouht.</L>
<L>Robyn wule Gilothe.</L>
<L>leden to &thorn;an ale.</L>
<L>And sitten &thorn;er to-gederes.</L>
<L N="76">and tellen heore tale.</L>
<L>He may quyten hire ale.</L>
<L>and seo&thorn;&thorn;e don &thorn;at gome.</L>
<L>An eue to go myd him.</L>
<L N="80">ne &thorn;inche&thorn; hire no schome.</L>
<L>Hire syre and hire dame.</L>
<L>&thorn;rete&thorn; hire to b&eacute;te.</L>
<L>Nule heo fur-go Robyn.</L>
<L N="84">for al heore &thorn;r&eacute;te.</L>
<L>Euer heo wule hire skere.</L>
<L>ne com hire no mon neyh.</L>
<L>Forte &thorn;at hire wombe.</L>
<L N="88">vp aryse an heyh.</L>
<L>Godemen for godes luue.</L>
<L>bi-leue&thorn; &oacute;ure sunne.</L>
<L>For at &thorn;on ende hit bi-nyme&thorn;.</L>
<L N="92">heoueryche wunne.</L>
<L>Bidde we seynte Marie.</L>
<L>for hire Milde mode.</L>
<L>For &thorn;e theres &thorn;at heo weop.</L>
<L N="96">for hire sune blode.</L>
<L>Al so wis. so he god is.</L>
<L>for hire erendynge.</L>
<L>To &thorn;e blysse of heouene.</L>
<L N="100">he vs alle brynge. Amen.</L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="26" TYPE="item">

<PB REF="00000208.tif" N="192">
<HEAD>XXVI. Will and Wit. [<I>Cotton MS. Caligula A ix, leaf</I> 246, <I>back.</I>]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hwenne so wil wit ofer-stie&eth;.</L>
<L>&THORN;enne is wil and wit for-lore.</L>
<L>Hwenne so wil his hete hie&eth;.</L>
<L N="4">&THORN;er nis nowiht wit icore.</L>
<L>Ofte wil to seor&yogh;e sie&eth;.</L>
<L>Bute &yogh;if wit him wite to-fore.</L>
<L>Ac hwenne so wil to wene wrie&eth;.</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;e o fo of wisdom is to-tore</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="27" TYPE="item">
<HEAD>XXVII. A Prayer to our Lady. [<I>Additional MS.</I> 27,909.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Leuedi sainte marie moder and meide.</L>
<L>&thorn;u wisie me nu&thorn;e for ich eom eirede.</L>
<L>vnnut lif to longe ich lede.</L>
<L N="4">hwanne ich me bi&thorn;enche; wel sore ich me a-drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ich eom i-bunde sore mid wel feole seonne.</L>
<L>mid smale and mid grete mid wel feole cunne.</L>
<L>dai and nicht ich fundie to wendende heonne.</L>
<L N="8">wielde Godd an heuene to hwucchere wunne.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Slep me ha&eth; mi lif forstole richt half o&eth;er more.</L>
<L>awai to late ich was iwar. nu hit me reowe&eth; sore</L>
<L>inne slepe ne wende ich endie nocht &thorn;ech ich slepe euremore.</L>
<L N="12">hwao se life&eth; &thorn;at wakerur beo &thorn;enc&thorn; of mine sore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al to longe slep&eth; &thorn;e mann &thorn;at neure nele awakie.</L>
<L>hwo se understant wel his ende-dai wel &yogh;eorne he mot spakie
<PB REF="00000209.tif" N="193"></L>
<L>to donde sunne awei fram him and fele almesse makie.</L>
<L N="16">&yogh;if him ne schal hwanne he for&eth; want; his brei gurdel quakie.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Slep me ha&eth; mi lif forstole er ich me bisehe.</L>
<L>&thorn;at ich wel a&yogh;itte nu bi suh&eth;e of min ehe.</L>
<L>mi brune her is hwit bicume. ich not for hwucche leihe.</L>
<L N="20">and mi tohte rude iturnd al in-to o&eth;re dehe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ifurn ich habbe isunehed mid worke and mid worde.</L>
<L>hwile in mine bedde and hwile atte borde.</L>
<L N="23">ofte win idrunke and selde of &thorn;e forde.</L>
<L>muchel ich habbe ispened; to lite ich habbe an horde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hord &thorn;at ich telle. is almesse-dede.</L>
<L>&yogh;ieue &thorn;e hungrie mete and te nakede iwede.</L>
<L>rede &thorn;e redliese &thorn;at is wi&eth;-ute rede.</L>
<L N="28">luuie god almichti and of him habbe drede.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ifurn ich habbe isune&yogh;et mid wurken and midd mu&eth;e.</L>
<L>and mid alle mine lime si&eth;&eth;e ich sunehi cu&eth;e.</L>
<L>and wel feole sunne ido &thorn;e me of&thorn;inche&eth; nu&eth;e.</L>
<L N="32">and swo me hadde ifurn ido &yogh;if hit me crist i-&yogh;u&eth;e.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Moder ful of milce ibidde mi mod wende.</L>
<L>l&aelig;te me steowi mi flesc and mine fo schiende.</L>
<L>edmodnesse luuie to mine lifes ende.</L>
<L N="36">luue to gode and te mann ic bidde &thorn;at tu me sende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Leuedi sainte marie understond nu seonne mine.</L>
<L>ber min erende wel to deore sune &thorn;ine.</L>
<L>hwas fle[s]ch and blod ihal&yogh;ed is of bred. of water of wine.</L>
<L N="40">&thorn;at us ischulde he eure; fram alle helle pine.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Inne mete and inne drinke ic habbe ibeo ouerdede.</L>
<L>and inne wel sittende schon in pruttere iwede.</L>
<L N="43">hwanne ich ihurde of gode speke. ne hedd ich hwat me sede.</L>
<L>hwan ich hier-of rekeni schal; wel sore me mei drede
</L>
</LG>

</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="28" TYPE="item"><PB REF="00000210.tif" N="194">
<HEAD>XXVIII. A Song to the Virgin. [<I>Egerton MS.</I> 613, <I>leaf</I> 2.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of on &thorn;at is so fayr and bri&yogh;t.</L>
<L><I>velud maris stella</I>.</L>
<L>Bri&yogh;ter &thorn;an &thorn;e day-is li&yogh;t.</L>
<L N="4"><I>parens</I> et <I>puella</I>.</L>
<L>Ic crie to &thorn;e &thorn;ou se to me.</L>
<L>Leuedy preye &thorn;i sone for me.</L>
<L><I>tam pia</I>.</L>
<L N="8">&THORN;at ic mote come to &thorn;e;</L>
<L><I>maria</I>.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of kare conseil &thorn;ou ert best.</L>
<L><I>felix fecundata</I>.</L>
<L N="12">Of alle wery &thorn;ou ert rest.</L>
<L><I>mater honorata</I>.</L>
<L>Bi-sek him wiz milde mod.</L>
<L>&THORN;at for ous alle sad is blod.</L>
<L N="16">in <I>cruce</I>.</L>
<L>&THORN;at we moten komen til him.</L>
<L><I>In luce</I>.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Al &thorn;is world was for-lore.</L>
<L N="20"><I>eua peccatrice;</I></L>
<L>Tyl our lord was y-bore;</L>
<L><I>de te</I> genitrice.</L>
<L>With aue it went a-way.</L>
<L N="24">&THORN;uster nyth and comet &thorn;e day</L>
<L><I>salutis</I></L>
<L>&THORN;e welle springet hut of &thorn;e;</L>
<L><I>uirtutis</I>.
<PB REF="00000211.tif" N="195"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L N="28">Leuedi flour of alle &thorn;ing.</L>
<L><I>rosa</I> sine <I>spina.</I></L>
<L>&THORN;u bere ihesu heuene king.</L>
<L>gratia <I>diuina</I>.</L>
<L N="32">Of alle &thorn;u berst &thorn;e pris.</L>
<L>Leuedi quene of parays.</L>
<L><I>electa.</I></L>
<L>Mayde milde. Moder.</L>
<L N="36"><I>es effecta.</I></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wel he wot he is &thorn;i sone.</L>
<L><I>uentre</I> quem <I>portasti</I>.</L>
<L>He wyl nout werne &thorn;e &thorn;i bone.</L>
<L N="40">paruum quem <I>lactasti;</I></L>
<L>So hende and so god he his.</L>
<L>He hauet brout ous to blis.</L>
<L>superni.</L>
<L N="44">&THORN;at hauez hi-dut &thorn;e foule put.</L>
<L><I>inferni.</I></L>
<TRAILER><I>Explicit</I> cantus <I>iste</I>.</TRAILER>
</LG>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="29" TYPE="item">
<HEAD>XXIX. A Prayer to the Virgin. [<I>Egerton MS</I>. 613, <I>leaf</I> 2.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>[I]blessed beo &thorn;u lauedi ful of houene. Blisse.</L>
<L>swete flur of parais moder of milder[t]nisse.</L>
<L>&thorn;u praie ihesu crist &thorn;i sone &thorn;at he me i-wisse.</L>
<L N="4">ware a londe al swo ihc beo &thorn;at he me ne i-misse.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Of &thorn;e faire lauedi min oreisun ich wile bi-ginnen.</L>
<L>&thorn;i deore swete sunnes loue. &thorn;u lere me to winnen.</L>
<L>wel ofte ich sike and sorwe make ne mai ich neuere blinnen</L>
<L N="8">bote &thorn;u &thorn;ruh &thorn;in milde mod bringe me out of sunne.
<PB REF="00000212.tif" N="196"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ofte ihc seke merci &thorn;in swete name ich calle</L>
<L>mi flehs is foul &thorn;is world is fals &thorn;u loke &thorn;at ich ne falle.</L>
<L N="11">Lauedi freo &thorn;u schild me fram &thorn;e pine of helle.</L>
<L>And send me in-to &thorn;at blisse &thorn;at tunge ne mai tellen.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mine werkes lauedi heo makie&thorn; me ful won.</L>
<L>wel ofte ich clepie and calle &thorn;u iher me for&thorn;an.</L>
<L>Bote ic chabbe &thorn;e help of &thorn;e o&thorn;er i ne kan.</L>
<L N="16">help &thorn;u me ful wel &thorn;u mist<NOTE PLACE="foot">Read <I>miht</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;u helpest mani a man.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Iblessed beo &thorn;u lauedi so fair and so briht.</L>
<L>Al min hope is uppon &thorn;e bi dai and bi nicht.</L>
<L>helpe &thorn;ruh &thorn;in milde mod for wel wel &thorn;u mist<NOTE PLACE="foot">Read <I>miht</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L N="20">&thorn;at ich neuere for feondes sake fur-go &thorn;in eche liht.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Briht and scene quen of houene ich bidde &thorn;in sunnes hore</L>
<L>&thorn;e sunnes &thorn;at ich habbe i-cvn heo rewwe&thorn;<NOTE PLACE="foot"><I>Or</I> re&thorn;&thorn;e&thorn;.</NOTE> me ful sore<MILESTONE N="2b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>wel ofte ich chabbe &thorn;e fur-saken. &thorn;e wil ich neuer eft more.</L>
<L N="24">Lauedi for &thorn;ine sake treu&thorn;en feondes lore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Iblessed beo &thorn;u lauedi so feir and so hende.</L>
<L>&thorn;u praie ihesu crist &thorn;i sone. &thorn;at he me i-sende.</L>
<L>whare a londe alswo ich beo er ich honne wende<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. &thorn;ende.</NOTE></L>
<L N="28">&thorn;at ich mote in parais wonien wi-&thorn;uten ende.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bricht and scene quen of storre so me liht and lere</L>
<L>in &thorn;is false fikele world so me led and steore.</L>
<L>&thorn;at ich at min ende-dai ne habbe non feond to fere.</L>
<L N="32">ihesu mit ti swete blod &thorn;u bohtest ful me deore.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu seinte marie sone &thorn;u iher &thorn;in moder bone</L>
<L>to &thorn;e ne dar i clepien noht to hire ich make min mene.</L>
<L N="35">&thorn;u do &thorn;at ich for hire sake beo imaked so clene</L>
<L>&thorn;at ich noht at dai of dome beo flemed of &thorn;in exsene.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="30" TYPE="item"><PB REF="00000213.tif" N="197">
<HEAD>XXX. A Song on the Passion. [<I>Egerton MS.</I> 613, <I>leaf</I> 1, <I>back</I>.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Somer is comen and winter gon,</L>
<L>&thorn;is day biginniz to longe,</L>
<L>and &thorn;is foules euerichon</L>
<L N="4">Ioye hem wit songe;</L>
<L>So stronge kare me bint,</L>
<L>al wit Ioye &thorn;at is funde</L>
<L>in londe,</L>
<L N="8">Al for a child</L>
<L>&thorn;at is so milde</L>
<L>of honde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;at child &thorn;at is so milde and wlong,</L>
<L N="12">and eke of grete munde,</L>
<L>bo&thorn;e in boskes and in bank,</L>
<L>isout me hauet astunde.</L>
<L>Ifunde he heuede me,</L>
<L N="16">for an appel of a tre,</L>
<L>ibunde;</L>
<L>[H]e brac &thorn;e bond</L>
<L>&thorn;at was so strong,</L>
<L N="20">wit wunde.
<PB REF="00000214.tif" N="198"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&thorn;at child &thorn;at was so wilde and wlong</L>
<L>to me a-lute lowe,</L>
<L>fram me to giwes he was sold,</L>
<L N="24">ne cu&thorn;en hey him nout cnowe</L>
<L>do we, sayden he,</L>
<L>naile we him opon a tre</L>
<L>alowe;</L>
<L N="28">Ac arst we</L>
<L>sullen scumi him</L>
<L>a&thorn;rowe.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ihesu is &thorn;e childes name,</L>
<L N="32">king of al[le] londe;</L>
<L>of &thorn;e king he meden game</L>
<L>and smiten him wit honde</L>
<L>to fonden him; opon a tre</L>
<L N="36">he &yogh;euen him wundes to and &thorn;re</L>
<L>mi[d] honden,</L>
<L>of bitter drunk</L>
<L>he senden him</L>
<L N="40">asonde.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>det he nom ho rode tre,</L>
<L>&thorn;e lif of us alle;</L>
<L>[ne miitte] it nowtt o&thorn;er be,</L>
<L N="44">bote we scolden walle;</L>
<L>and wallen in helle dep</L>
<L>nere neuere so swet</L>
<L>wit alle.</L>
<L N="48">ne miitte us</L>
<L>saui castel, tur,</L>
<L>ne halle.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Mayde and Moder &thorn;at astod,</L>
<L N="52">marie ful of grace,</L>
<L>[O hu let &thorn;e teres al of blod]</L>
<L>uallen in &thorn;e place;
<PB REF="00000215.tif" N="199"></L>
<L>&thorn;e trace ran of he blod</L>
<L N="56">changedere fles and blod</L>
<L>and face.</L>
<L>he was to-drawe</L>
<L>so dur islawe</L>
<L N="60">in chace.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>det he nam, &thorn;e suete man,</L>
<L>wel heye opon &thorn;e rode;</L>
<L>he wes hure sunnes euerichon</L>
<L N="64">mid is swete blode;</L>
<L>mid flode he lute adun</L>
<L>and brace<NOTE PLACE="foot">Read <I>brac</I>.</NOTE> &thorn;e &yogh;ates of &thorn;at prisun</L>
<L>&thorn;at stode,</L>
<L N="68">and ches hem out</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ere were</L>
<L>gode.</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>he ros him ene &thorn;e &thorn;ridde day,</L>
<L N="72">and sette him on is trone,</L>
<L>he wule come a domes day</L>
<L>to demus euerichic one.</L>
<L>grone he may and wepen ay,</L>
<L N="76">&thorn;e man &thorn;at deiet wit-oute lay,</L>
<L>alone.</L>
<L>grante ous, crist,</L>
<L>wit &thorn;in uprist</L>
<L N="80">to gone.<NOTE PLACE="foot">MS. gene.</NOTE> Amen.
</L>
</LG>

</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="31" TYPE="item"><PB REF="00000216.tif" N="200">
<HEAD>XXXI. The Ten Commandments. [<I>Cambr. Univ. Libr. MS. Ff.</I> 6. 15, <I>leaf</I> 21; <I>before</I> 1300.<NOTE PLACE="foot">In the left margin of the MS.</NOTE>]</HEAD> 
<HEADNOTE><P>De .x. preceptis in lingua materna. Printed in 'A Catalogue of the Manuscripts preserved in the Library of the University of Cambridge,' vol. ii. p. 522.</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&THORN;u salt hauen na god buten An.</L>
<L>Idel adh ne swere &thorn;u Nan.</L>
<L>&THORN;e halidayes &thorn;u shalt &thorn;ieme.</L>
<L N="4">ffader and moder &thorn;u shalt queme.</L>
<L>Loke &thorn;at tu ne sla na man.</L>
<L>Leccherie do &thorn;u nan.</L>
<L>Be na &thorn;ef. ne &thorn;eues fere.</L>
<L N="8">ffals witnesse &thorn;u ne bere.</L>
<L>&THORN;ierne<NOTE PLACE="foot">Printed &thorn;reune. 'Non concupisces rem proximi tui' in the Latin version opposite the English.</NOTE> &thorn;u nout &thorn;in nethtebure hus.</L>
<L>Noch &thorn;at his is. ne his spus.</L>
</LG>
</DIV1>
